{[%evp 0,25,36,10,60,44,44,42,90,71,96,46,46,52,51,54,51,65,58,68,58,63,69,25,
96,68,74,77]} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 g6 {This is a combination of the
Caro-Kann and Modern/Pirc lines. Black allows us to get full control over the
center and is hoping to outplay us positionally.} (3... e6 {This is a terrible
mix of the French and Caro-Kann.} 4. d4 Bb4 5. e5 Ne7 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 $14 {
We have a very good version of the Winawer. We can go a4 next and it will
transpose to my repertoire against the French but with one full tempo up.}) (
3... a6 {I am being forced to analyse this because Magnus played it in a few
games recently :) Of course, it was mostly blitz but let us figure out how to
exploit it.} 4. d4 Bg4 {This is a worse version of the 3...Bg4 variation which
we will see starting from the 3rd chapter.} 5. h3 {We are going after the
light-squared bishop.} Bxf3 (5... Bh5 6. g4 Bg6 7. exd5 cxd5 8. Ne5 $16 {
With h4 to follow, White is clearly better.}) 6. Qxf3 e6 7. Bf4 {This is the
best square for the bishop and we are going to castle queenside next. We want
to really punish such careless play by Black.} Nf6 8. O-O-O $146 {We waill
maintain the tension for as long as possible.} (8. e5 $2 {is too soon. Black
gets to immediately counter attack our centre.} Nfd7 $36 {[%cal Gc6c5] 1/2-1/2
(44) Robson,R (2567)-Jobava,B (2696) Khanty-Mansiysk 2009}) 8... b5 9. Bd3 b4
10. Na4 Be7 11. Kb1 $14 {We have a nice edge and Black is struggling with his
king in the centre.}) (3... d4 {is quite bad after} 4. Ne2 c5 5. c3 $1 {
We immediate break Black's control over the centre.} Nc6 (5... dxc3 6. bxc3 Nc6
7. d4 $16 {[%cal Ge2g3]}) (5... d3 6. Nf4 {[%csl Rd3]}) 6. cxd4 cxd4 7. Qa4 $1
{An important move winning the pawn on d4. Black has no compensation for the
pawn.} Bd7 8. Nexd4 $16) 4. d4 Bg7 (4... Bg4 {This is a bit too early as we
can win the bishop and also consolidate our centre. We have a big lead in
development.} 5. h3 {We immediately force Black to give up this light-squared
bishop.} (5. Be2 {Is also good enough.}) 5... Bxf3 6. Qxf3 dxe4 {Black tries
to force the queen to e4 to defend the d4 pawn.} (6... e6 {Has been played
more but it just gives us a nice advantage in the centre.} 7. Bf4 {The bishop
is ready to jump to e5 as Black has weakened several dark squares around his
king.} Nf6 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Be5 $16) 7. Nxe4 $1 {Of course, we did not go for
h3 to take with the queen. Now Black has to take up the challenge and take on
d4.} (7. Qxe4 Nf6 $11) 7... Qxd4 8. Bd2 {Bc3 is a huge threat. The next couple
of moves are forced.} Nf6 9. Bc3 Qxe4+ 10. Qxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxh8 f6 {Black claims
that the bishop on h8 is trapped but we are in time to get the bishop out.} 12.
h4 $1 Nd7 13. h5 g5 14. h6 $14 {[%cal Gh8g7] Next we will exchange the bishops
and end up with an exchange up.}) 5. h3 {Now we stop the move Bg4 and secure
our kingside. Many years ago I attended a camp where we discussed some of the
sidelines for Black such as the Alekhine and Scandinavian. I realised that one
of the major problems that Black faces in these structures is the bishop on c8.
It lacks a good square along the c8-h3 diagonal. That is the reason why Black
sometimes plays Bg4 and takes on f3 to trade it off. We do not allow that.}
dxe4 (5... Nh6 {I never understood this move. The knight does not do much on
f5 anyway.} 6. Bf4 f6 (6... O-O 7. e5 $1 f6 8. Qd2 Nf7 9. O-O-O {transposes}) (
6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 Nf5 8. c3 O-O 9. Bd3 Nd6 10. O-O Nxe4 11. Bxe4 {I have no
idea what Black has achieved by exchanging the knights after wasting 3 moves.}
Nd7 12. Re1 Nf6 13. Bd3 Be6 {This was another typical example which we
analysed during the previously mentioned camp. The bishop is not well placed
on e6 due to} 14. Rxe6 $1 fxe6 15. Qe2 $16 {[%cal Ga1e1,Gf3g5] Black is under
a lot of trouble along the light squares, e6 in particular.}) 7. Qd2 Nf7 8.
O-O-O O-O 9. e5 $1 {With the centre in our control, we can now look to start
our play on the kingside.} fxe5 (9... b5 10. Re1 Na6 11. h4 $18) 10. dxe5 Na6
11. h4 $1 {There are other ways to play but I like the direct approach.} Bg4
12. Re1 Bxf3 13. gxf3 d4 {Black has to do something quickly as we are very
close to breaking through on the kingside.} 14. Nb1 Qd5 15. h5 Nxe5 16. Bxe5
Bxe5 17. Bc4 $1 {Winning the dark-squared bishop is crucial here.} Qxc4 18.
Rxe5 $16 {Black is forced to liquidate with d3 but we have a big edge in the
resulting endgame.}) (5... Nf6 {Black forces us to release the tension.} 6. e5
Ne4 (6... Nfd7 7. Bf4 $16 {We will follow up with Qd2 and maybe h4-h5 later.})
7. a4 $1 $146 {This has never been played even though there were more than
1100 games in the database. What is the point? We stop Black's idea of going
for the move c5 immediately by preparing the move Bb5. It also allows us to go
for Ba3 in the future. Another point is that Qa5-a4 ideas are no longer
possible.} (7. Bd3 {allows} Nxc3 8. bxc3 c5 $1 9. O-O c4 10. Be2 Qa5 11. Bd2
Nc6 $11 {[%cal Ga5a4]}) (7. Nxe4 {is the main line but it leads to a lot of
forcing lines.}) 7... O-O (7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 c5 9. Bb5+ $16) (7... c5 8. Bb5+
Nc6 9. dxc5 $16) 8. Bd3 {Now the plan of Nxc3 and c5 is not as effective as we
can just develop normally. c4 and Qa5 can even be met with Qd2 followed by Ba3.
Having the pawn on a4 helps us here. This is very similar to my recommendation
in the database against the French.} Nxc3 (8... Qa5 9. O-O Nxc3 10. bxc3 c5 (
10... Qxc3 {is way too greedy} 11. Bd2 Qb2 12. Rb1 Qa2 13. Qc1 Qxa4 14. Ra1 $18
) 11. Bd2 {Keeps queens on the board. Having played a4 we are not so afraid of
Black going c4.} (11. Qd2 {is simple and Black has to trade into an unpleasant
endgame very soon.} Nc6 12. Re1 cxd4 13. cxd4 Qxd2 14. Bxd2 $14) 11... c4 12.
Be2 $14 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gh3h4]}) 9. bxc3 c5 10. O-O c4 11. Be2 f6 {Black has to
try and create some counterplay.} (11... Qa5 12. Qd2 $16 {[%cal Gc1a3]}) 12.
Re1 Nc6 13. exf6 exf6 14. Nh2 {[%cal Ge2f3,Ga1b1,Gc1a3,Gh2g4,Gg4e3] We have
easy play here and several different ideas. The d5 pawn is a long-term issue
for Black.}) 6. Nxe4 Nf6 (6... Nd7 7. a4 $5 $146 {This is the 2nd time in this
chapter that we are looking at the same novelty. There have been more than
1500 games in this position but a4 was never played. What is the point of this
move? We do not commit our bishop to either c4 or d3 and wait for Black to
show his hand with either exf6 or Nxf6.} (7. Bc4 {Was my plan initially} Ngf6 (
7... Nb6 8. Bb3 $16) 8. Nxf6+ exf6 $1 {This is the top choice of the computer.}
(8... Nxf6 {Most of them do go for this which gives us a pleasant advantage.}
9. O-O $16 {[%cal Gf1e1]}) 9. O-O O-O {[%cal Gf8e8,Gd7f8,Gf6f5]}) 7... Ngf6 8.
Nxf6+ Nxf6 ({We are ready to meet the move} 8... exf6 {with} 9. Qe2+ $1 Qe7 10.
Qxe7+ Kxe7 11. Bd2 {We exchange of the queens and this makes it much easier
for us to make use of our better pawn structure on the queenside. Moreover,
the Black king is still not perfectly safe.} Rd8 12. O-O-O Nb6 13. c4 {[%cal
Gd2b4]} Kf8 14. Bd3 $14 {We will go a5 and Rhe1 next. We can always go b3 too.}
) 9. Bc4 O-O 10. O-O Bf5 11. Re1 $14 {We can go Ne5 and c3 next. What is the
bishop doing on f5?}) 7. Nxf6+ exf6 {I think that this is the best that Black
can do in this variation. However compared to the 3...dxe4 and Nf6 variations
the bishop is worse on g7 than on d6.} (7... Bxf6 {White has a few different
options but I really like} 8. Bh6 $1 c5 9. d5 $1 Bxb2 10. Bc4 {We are not
afraid to give up the exchange to win the important dark-squared bishop.} Bc3+
11. Nd2 Nd7 12. O-O {[%cal Gd2e4]} Nb6 13. Qe2 (13. Ne4 $5 Be5 14. Qe2 $14 {
It is not going to be easy for Black to get his king to safety.}) 13... Bxd2
14. Bxd2 O-O 15. Rfe1 $14 {The dark squares are a huge problem for Black.}) 8.
Bd3 {This looks like a weird square for the bishop but we are planning to go
c4 soon and we want the 'e' file to be open.} O-O 9. O-O {There are quite a
few options here for Black. Our plan will remain the same. To go c4 and Re1
next followed by strengthening our centre.} Be6 (9... Na6 $6 {does not work
here with the bishop on g7.} 10. Bxa6 $146 (10. c3 {Paehtz, E (2513)-Howell, D
(2689) ENG 2018}) 10... bxa6 11. c4 Qb6 12. b3 a5 13. Re1 $16 {[%cal Gc1a3]}) (
9... Nd7 10. Re1 Re8 11. Rxe8+ Qxe8 12. c4 Nb6 13. Qb3 Be6 14. Bd2 {Next on
the agenda is to go a4-a5 and kick the knight back.}) (9... a5 {Black prepares
Na6.} 10. Re1 Na6 11. c4 Nc7 12. b3 {We stop the idea of a4 for Black. The
bishop can jump to a3 now at the right moment.} Re8 13. Rxe8+ Nxe8 14. Qc2 $14
{[%cal Gc1d2,Gd2c3,Ga1e1]}) (9... Re8 10. c4 Na6 {Black at least managed to
get Na6 in one go but it does not solve his problems.} 11. Re1 Nc7 12. Bd2 $14)
10. c4 Na6 11. Re1 Nc7 12. Qc2 Re8 13. b3 $14 {We have very good control over
the center and Black lacks a good plan. The bishop on g7 is misplaced and he
cannot go f5 easily without creating a big weakness on e5.} *

