{[%evp 0,39,19,45,59,44,44,43,68,51,51,44,29,33,30,-10,-9,-17,-3,-40,-33,-40,
-36,-41,-41,-67,-29,-20,33,-81,-53,-70,-51,-53,-10,-19,71,13,46,59,45,31]} 1.
e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 Nf6 {Black is forcing us to clarify the tension in the
centre. Of course, we take the chance to gain space with the move-} 4. e5 Ne4 {
Black will be happy to trade the knights off.} (4... Nfd7 {This is a worse
version of the French Steinitz. However, the knight is already on f3 and we
cannot go for f4. So we do need to know a few details here.} 5. d4 e6 6. Ng5 $1
{This has been played pretty rarely. We need to be very energetic to exploit
Black's play.} Be7 7. h4 h6 (7... O-O {Black is out of the frying pan into the
fire.} 8. Qh5 h6 9. Rh3 $18) 8. Nxe6 $1 {We do not let Black just castle.} fxe6
9. Qh5+ Kf8 10. Rh3 Qe8 (10... Kg8 11. Bd3 $18 {[%cal Gd3g6]}) 11. Rf3+ Nf6 12.
Qg4 $16 {We will win back the piece with a big edge.}) 5. Ne2 $1 {Not on his
terms! The immediate idea is to play d3 and kick the knight out. The other
plan is to take the knight to g3 and then force Black to open the 'h' or 'f'
file for our rook.} Qb6 {Black forces us to play the move d4, after which the
knight on e4 is more secure. Also, Black can quickly fight for the centre with
c5.} (5... Bg4 6. Nfg1 $1 {A creative idea. Unfortunately for Black, his
pieces are going to get pushed back with a lot of tempi next.} Nc5 7. d4 Nca6 {
A very nice and active square for the knight :)} 8. h3 {We will be harassing
the bishop next.} Bf5 9. g4 Bd7 10. c3 $16) (5... Bf5 6. d3 Nc5 7. Nfd4 {
The bishop lacks a good square.} Bd7 8. c3 $16) 6. d4 e6 (6... c5 {This is too
early. Black needs the bishop to come to c5.} 7. dxc5 Qxc5 8. Ned4 $16 {
[%cal Gc2c3,Gc1e3]}) 7. Ng3 c5 8. Bd3 $1 {This is the whole reason why this
line is not that popular for Black. We do not mind giving up the d4 pawn and
our main priority is to open up the 'f' file and start some initiative on the
kingside. Moreover, similar to the French the bishop is stuck behind the pawn
chain.} Nxg3 (8... Nc6 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Bxe4 cxd4 {transposes.}) (8... cxd4 {
Black allows us to win the pawn on e4 and the d4 pawn will come under fire
next.} 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Bxe4 Nc6 {This was played by Fabi in 2017. I think he
messed up his preparation somewhere.} (10... Bd7 $146 {Is the top choice of
the computer but gives us a good edge.} 11. Qxd4 Bc5 12. Qd2 $14) 11. O-O Bc5 (
11... Bd7 12. a3 h6 13. Re1 Rd8 {Happened in the game 1-0 (71) Short, N (2675)
-Caruana, F (2827) Caleta 2017. White went on to win the game.} 14. b4 $16) 12.
a3 a5 13. Qd2 $16 {We are not going after the 'd' pawn. We are going after
Black's kingside. Qf4, QG4 will follow next and White has a clear advantage.})
9. fxg3 $1 {We are going to castle next and make use of the 'f' file. We are
happy to allow Black to take on d4 with the pawn as it will keep his pieces
stuck on the kingside. One of my coaches used to call this "lack of
communication". Black is not able to bring his pieces to defend the kingside
easily.} (9. hxg3 cxd4 $11) 9... cxd4 {The traditional wisdom- if you going to
suffer, at least win some material.} (9... Nc6 {Black does not want to take on
d4 but we also just maintain the tension.} 10. O-O h6 11. dxc5 $1 {Now we can
take on c5 and also get our king to safety on h1. We have the 'f' file for
free.} Bxc5+ 12. Kh1 $16) 10. O-O Nc6 (10... h6 $2 {This was played by the
strong Chinese GM Wei Yi a couple of times in online blitz but the engine
screams +4 for us.} 11. Nh4 $1 {h6 has created a lot of weaknesses on the
kingside and Black is struggling to meet the threat of Qh5.} Nc6 12. Qh5 Nd8
13. g4 $1 $18 {We are breaking through with g5 next.}) 11. a3 {We want to gain
space and start our play on both sides of the board as Black has the option to
castle either side.} (11. Qe2 {is also possible but will mostly transpose.})
11... Bd7 (11... a5 {This is a huge weakness on the queenside.} 12. Qe2 {
Qe2 here always prepares the move Ng5, keeping an eye on the e5 pawn.} h6 (
12... Bd7 13. Ng5 $18) 13. g4 $1 {This is another typical idea. We want to
play g5 and Black is usually unable to allow Ng5 at any moment.} Bd7 14. g5
O-O-O 15. gxh6 gxh6 16. Bd2 $16 {Black has zero hopes to do anything on the
kingside while our play is much more obvious.}) (11... Be7 12. b4 a6 13. Qe2 {
Again we are preparing the move Ng5.} h6 {allows} (13... O-O 14. Ng5 $18) 14.
g4 $1 {[%cal Gg4g5]} Bd7 {transposes.}) 12. b4 {We want to go b5 next and
further kick back his pieces. If Black stops that we can focus on the kingside.
} a6 {This was necessary. Although now Black can hardly castle on the
queenside since we are ready to play the move b5.} (12... Be7 {allows} 13. b5
Na5 (13... Nd8 14. a4) 14. Ng5 $1 Bxg5 15. Bxg5 $18 {We are going to crush
Black on the dark squares.}) 13. Qe2 {Preparing Ng5.} h6 14. g4 $1 {We have
seen this idea before. Not easy to deal with the idea of g5.} g5 {A desperate
measure.} (14... Be7 15. g5 {If we take on h6, we forever ruin Black's hopes
of getting his king to safety somewhere.} hxg5 16. Nxg5 f5 17. exf6 Bxf6 18.
Nxe6 $16) 15. Bd2 Be7 16. Rac1 $5 {A nice prophylactic move aimed against the
plan of Qc7. We want to go c3 at the right moment.} (16. Be1 {Looks very
clever but it allows Black to create some play after} Qc7 $1 {The threat here
is the move h5 followed by g4, winning the pawn on e5.} (16... Rf8 {Bacrot,E 
(2671)-Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2626) Linares 2019} 17. Bf2 $16 {[%cal Gc2c3]})
17. h3 $14) 16... Qc7 17. h3 {Important to stop h5 and g4.} Na7 (17... O-O-O {
runs into} 18. c4 $18) 18. Qf2 {[%cal Gf3g5]} Bb5 19. Nxd4 O-O 20. Nf3 $16 {
[%cal Gh3h4] We want to go h4 next. White has a lot of initiative on the
kingside.} *

