{[%evp 0,31,45,28,59,60,56,43,109,40,47,45,68,2,42,39,38,45,82,26,33,33,35,40,
44,36,43,34,26,21,37,35,35,3]} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 Bg4 {This is the most
popular move in the position and is very principled. Black fights back in the
centre and does not allow us to gain full control over the centre. It leads to
more complex positions compared to 3...dxe4 and we will welcome that.} 4. h3 {
Immediately we force Black to make a decision regarding the bishop.} Bxf3 (4...
Bh5 {This has been played in several games but it is inaccurate. The bishop
will get misplaced on g6.} 5. exd5 cxd5 6. g4 {We force the bishop back.} Bg6
7. Ne5 {We want to go Bb5 next. The other idea is to go h4 and harass the
bishop on g6.} Nc6 (7... a6 8. h4 f6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. d4 $16 {The queen will
go to d3 next and we are much better.}) 8. d4 e6 (8... f6 {Black forces us to
release the tension early. This was played against me by GM Delchev a couple
of years back.} 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qd3 {It is not clear where we need our
light-squared bishop and this helps us prepare the move 0-0-0.} Kf7 11. Be3 e6
12. O-O-O Rc8 13. Kb1 {Our king is pretty safe now and we will go h4-h5 very
soon.} Na5 14. Bc1 Bd6 15. h4 Ne7 {All of this happened in my game 1/2-1/2 (20)
Arjun, K (2477)-Delchev, A (2521) Arandjelovac 2021. I could have maintained
my big edge with the creative-} 16. Nb5 $1 {We misplace the bishop to b8.
Black has to waste a tempo to go a6 next.} Bb8 17. h5 Qb6 18. Qf3 $16) 9. h4 f6
(9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Bb4 11. h5 Be4 12. Bb5+ Kf8 13. Rh3 $16 {We will continue
with Bd2 next and win one of the bishops.}) 10. h5 $5 {Maybe not the topmost
choice of the computers but I like the resulting positions.} (10. Nxc6 {
is also pretty good}) 10... fxe5 {This is not the most common move but
objectively the best. Black at least gets control over the centre.} (10... Bf7
{This is just sad for Black with a cramped position, playing against the
bishop pair.} 11. Nxf7 Kxf7 12. a3 {We just stop all ideas of Bb4 or Nb4. Next,
we will continue with Be3, Bd3, Qf3 and we can castle either side.} Bd6 13. Be3
Nge7 14. Bd3 $16) 11. hxg6 h6 12. dxe5 Bb4 $1 {Black has to develop quickly.
No time to go treasure hunting.} 13. Bd2 Nge7 (13... Nxe5 14. Qe2 $18) 14. g5 {
We also need to play energetically. The position is quite dynamic with
contrasting features for both sides.} Bxc3 15. bxc3 Qc7 16. gxh6 (16. f4 Nf5
17. Bd3 Nce7 {I do not want to allow this kind of a blockade.}) 16... Qxe5+ 17.
Qe2 {We are okay with trading the queens with our bishop pair.} gxh6 18. O-O-O
Qxe2 19. Bxe2 Nxg6 20. c4 O-O-O 21. Bg4 Kc7 22. Bxe6 dxc4 23. f4 {We have a
slight edge in the endgame. It is not easy for Black to play against our
bishops.}) 5. Qxf3 {We have already won the bishop pair but Black is very
solid. We would like to just develop with d4, Bd3 but unfortunately, the d4
pawn is a big issue. So usually we continue with Be2, 0-0 first before
deciding on future plans. We wait for Black to commit his pieces.} e6 (5... Nf6
{Both move orders are possible but I think this is less flexible as Black is
committing his knight to f6.} 6. Be2 {We usually go for d4 only when Black
plays the move Nd7 blocking the queen on d8 or if Black gets his bishop to c5.}
(6. d4 dxe4 {[%csl Rd4]} 7. Qe3 e6 {This is too solid.}) 6... dxe4 (6... e5 7.
d3 d4 8. Nb1 $14 {The move e5 is definitely in our favour in these positions
and we will go Qg3 followed by maybe h4-h5 next.}) (6... d4 7. Nb1 e6 8. d3 Bd6
9. Nd2 Nbd7 10. h4 h5 11. Qh3 $14) 7. Nxe4 Nxe4 8. Qxe4 Qd5 {Black is eager to
trade the queens off. We do not mind it terribly since the bishop pair is
supposed to be very good in the endgames.} (8... Nd7 {We will see similar
lines in the future and we get a very pleasant position with the bishop pair.}
9. d4 Nf6 10. Qd3 $14) 9. Qxd5 {I like the resulting pawn structure for White.}
(9. d3 $5 $146 e6 10. Bf4 Be7 11. h4 h5 12. Be5 Kf8 $1 {[%cal Gb8d7]}) (9. Qg4
Nd7 10. O-O e6 11. d4 {1/2-1/2 (14) Puranik,A (2550)-Sulskis,S (2519) Riga 2019
} h5 $1 12. Qf4 Bd6 $11) 9... cxd5 10. d4 Nc6 11. Be3 g6 12. g4 $1 {It is
important to get control over the kingside.} (12. c3 h5 $11) 12... Bg7 (12...
h5 $5 13. gxh5 gxh5 14. h4 $14 {[%csl Rh5]}) 13. c3 {We will follow up with
0-0-0 and then eventually go for h4-h5 in the kingside. We have a nice
risk-free edge in the position.}) 6. Be2 {This is the third most played move
in the position but it is very topical these days. I always believe that when
we have a choice we should go for the most necessary move to remain very
flexible. We want to castle kingside first. White does not intend to go d4
unless Black goes for either Nd7 or Bc5. We will see how Black develops his
pieces.} Nd7 {Black blocks his queen thus allowing us to get control over the
centre with-} (6... g6 {This is too slow.} 7. d4 Bg7 (7... dxe4 $6 8. Nxe4 {
Black cannot go after the pawn on d4.} Qxd4 9. Be3 $18 {[%cal Ga1d1]}) 8. Bf4
$1 {Black cannot take on d4 and otherwise this is the best square for our
bishop.} Nf6 9. e5 Nfd7 10. h4 h5 11. O-O-O {It's not easy for Black to find a
safe place for the king.} c5 12. Bg5 Qa5 13. Nxd5 $1 {It's time to break
through!} exd5 14. e6 O-O (14... fxe6 15. Bd3 Nf8 16. Rhe1 $16) 15. exd7 Nxd7
16. Qxd5 $14 {We have an extra pawn and a nice edge.}) (6... d4 $5 {This is
possible on several different moves. I like this structure for us as our plans
are very simple. We will go Nb1, d3, Nd2 followed by either h4, Qh3 or g3, Qg2
and f4.} 7. Nb1 Nd7 (7... Nf6 8. d3 Bd6 9. Nd2 O-O 10. O-O a5 11. g3 $14 {
[%cal Gf3g2,Gf2f4]}) (7... c5 8. Qg3 $1 {The bishop is now stuck on f8.} Nc6 9.
d3 $14) (7... Ne7 8. d3 Ng6 9. g3 h5 $1 {I faced this last year and my
opponent was very well prepared. But I had analysed these positions well- not
concrete moves but the general plans and ideas. I feel these positions are
much easier to play for us in a practical game.} (9... c5 {This gives us very
easy play and a nice edge-} 10. Qg2 Nc6 11. O-O $14) 10. h4 a5 {This is the
top choice of computers. He wants to gain space on the queenside. I will show
you my game as the main line but you can deviate with 11.Nd2 or 11.Bf1.} 11.
O-O (11. Bf1 $5 {[%cal Gf1h3,Gb1d2]}) (11. Nd2 {This was there in my notes but
I did not remember the concrete details.} a4 12. a3 Nd7 13. Bf1 $1 Be7 14. Bh3
$14 {The bishop is quite well placed here and we can now continue with Qe2,
Nf3, 0-0.}) 11... a4 12. Qg2 {I am completely ignoring his plan on the
queenside. After this point, he started slowing down while I was still
blitzing ;) I was just following my instincts and the general plan.} Nd7 13. f4
e5 14. f5 Ne7 15. c3 c5 $6 (15... Qb6 16. Qf2 Nc8 $1 17. cxd4 Qxd4 18. Qxd4
exd4 19. Bf4 {White still has some initiative in this endgame.}) 16. Na3 $1 $14
{Now we get the juicy b5 square for the knight and Black's troubles continue.
1-0 (73) Arjun,K (2499)-Kochavi, O (2356) Novi Sad 2022}) 8. d3 (8. Qg3 h5 $1
$11) 8... Bd6 9. h4 $1 {This is the other typical plan in the position- we put
our queen on h3.} (9. O-O {is also possible}) 9... h5 10. Qh3 Ngf6 (10... Ne7 {
0-1 (45) Dragnev,V (2535) -Riazantsev,A (2634) Warsaw 2021} 11. O-O Ng6 12. g3
{[%csl Rh5] Black is unable to castle and we have a nice edge.}) 11. Nd2 $14 {
We will continue with 0-0 next and the bishop pair gives us a slight edge in
these positions.} Bc7 12. O-O {Now we want to go f4 next and start our play on
the kingside and the centre.} e5 {Black had to stop it immediately.} 13. c3 $1
{With the black king still in the center we want to open up the files.} Nc5 14.
cxd4 {I decided to play it safe in my game since I was not in the best form at
that moment.} (14. Nb3 $5 Ne6 (14... Nxb3 15. axb3 $14) 15. cxd4 Nxd4 16. Nxd4
Qxd4 17. Qg3 {We force Black to make weaknesses on the kingside.} g6 18. Bg5
Nd7 19. Rab1 $14 {We want to go b4 next. Black's king lacks a good square on
the board.} a5 20. Be3 Qd6 21. Rfd1 Nf6 22. Rbc1) 14... Qxd4 15. Nf3 Qd7 16.
Qxd7+ Nfxd7 17. Be3 Ne6 (17... Bb6 $1 {was better not allowing us to go for
the move d4.} 18. Rac1 Ne6 19. Rfd1 {We will go for d4 next. We have a more
pleasant position.}) 18. d4 exd4 19. Nxd4 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 $14 {I had a very
pleasant advantage but was not very ambitious and ended up making a draw very
soon 1/2-1/2 (39) Arjun, K (2529) -Narayanan,S (2657) chess24.com INT 2022}) 7.
d4 dxe4 (7... Qb6 {Is too greedy} 8. Bf4 $1 Qxd4 9. exd5 exd5 10. Rd1 Qb6 11.
O-O {We have a big lead in development and Black's king is in trouble.} Ngf6
12. Bd3 O-O-O 13. Rb1 $1 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4] Once b4-b5 happens we will have a
nice initiative.}) 8. Nxe4 Ngf6 9. Nd2 $5 {We have more space and I like to
preserve the minor pieces on the board. This is the general rule- the side
with space advantage should not trade minor pieces. This is because with less
space those minor pieces get cramped and lack the freedom to move around.} (9.
Nxf6+ {Is also possible- followed by c3.}) 9... Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Rd1 {
The rook is well placed here as we are expecting Black to go for a pawn break
with either c5 or e5.} a5 (11... Qc7 12. Nc4 {We want to go for Bf4 next.} Nd5
13. Ne3 Rad8 14. c3 Rfe8 15. Bd3 h6 16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. g3 {We have a slight
edge with the bishop pair.}) (11... Qa5 12. Nc4 Qd5 13. Qb3 Nb6 {1-0 (21)
Vachier Lagrave,M (2780)-Ducarmon,Q (2479) Chess.com INT 2019} 14. Ne5 Qxb3 15.
axb3 $16 {White is quite a bit better, especially with this pawn structure on
the queenside.}) (11... e5 $5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Qg3 Bd6 14. Nf3 Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3
Qe7 16. Bd3 $14 {The pawn structure is symmetrical but we undeniably have a
small edge with the pair of bishops.}) 12. a4 Nb6 13. c3 Qd5 14. Qg3 (14. Qd3
Rfd8 15. Nf3 $14 {1/2-1/2 (30) Sindarov,J (2587)-Cori, J (2655) Riga 2021})
14... Qd6 15. Qxd6 Bxd6 16. Kf1 $14 {We have a very pleasant endgame ahead of
us.} *

