{[%evp 0,47,28,37,56,56,53,48,69,54,32,32,64,17,69,80,73,66,50,50,50,7,19,-14,
4,12,22,23,12,27,22,44,40,45,45,0,48,41,37,-104,-79,-80,-73,-69,-81,-53,-53,
-53,-53,-86]} 1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 Bg4 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Be2 Bc5 $5
{This is the 3rd most popular move in the position but it was recommended by
Erwin l'Ami in his course on the Caro-Kann. It has since become quite popular
and I have faced it in numerous games both online and OTB. What is the point?
Black will next develop his knight to e7 and not allow us to get d4 easily.} 7.
Qg3 {This has been played in less than 10% of the games but I think that it is
the most dangerous weapon against Black's system.} (7. O-O Ne7 8. Rd1 d4 $1 $11
{This is a much better version of the lines we saw in the previous chapter.})
7... Bd4 {This is practically forced. Here I had a few ideas in mind. I will
give you two promising options with contrasting styles. I like when we have
two different stylistic approaches to the same position as we can decide based
on our opponent.} (7... g6 {This looks bad but I have faced this in a few
blitz games against strong players.} 8. exd5 $1 cxd5 (8... exd5 9. Qe5+ $18) 9.
Nb5 $1 {This is the point. We have dual threats. We want to get both Nc7 and
Qc3 exploiting the long diagonal.} Na6 10. d4 Be7 11. O-O $18 {We will meet
Nf6 with Bh6 and not allow Black to castle easily. Otherwise, we are going to
go c4 next.}) 8. exd5 {This is the more solid option and will be my main
recommendation. It has been played in only 5 games in total.} (8. d3 $5 {
This has also been played only around 5 times. What is the plan here? I want
to go Bd1, Ne2 next and also maintain the tension in the centre.} Ne7 (8... Nd7
{This is not accurate due to} 9. Be3 $1 {Black has problems with the g7 pawn.}
Qb6 (9... Bxe3 10. fxe3 {The open 'f' file is great news for us. It also helps
us control the centre better.} g6 11. O-O-O Ne7 12. h4 $14) (9... Bf6 10. d4
$14) 10. O-O {We are now threatening Na4. Black has to release the tension.}
Bxe3 (10... Be5 {Only helps us push our 'f' pawn for free.} 11. f4 Bd4 12. Bxd4
Qxd4+ 13. Kh1 $14 {[%cal Gf4f5]}) 11. fxe3 g6 12. d4 {We have nice control
over the centre and Black still has to struggle to castle either side.} Ne7 13.
Rab1 O-O 14. Qd6 Qd8 15. Bd3 $14) 9. Bd1 {The simple continuation of our plan.
I have played this in a few blitz games and usually get the ideal regrouping
with Ne2, c3, Bc2 and maybe Qf3, Ng3. I think practically it is not easy to
react accurately with Black.} (9. Be3 Bxe3 10. fxe3 O-O $11) (9. h4 {Is an
interesting move which I have played before. You can check this out on your
own.} Nd7 10. h5 h6 11. Nd1 dxe4 12. dxe4 Bf6 $6 13. O-O e5 14. Ne3 Bg5 15. Nc4
f6 16. Nd6+ Kf8 17. Qb3 Nd5 18. Nxb7 {1-0 (18) Arjun,K (2477)-Koustav,C (2431)
Lichess.org INT 2020}) 9... Nd7 $1 {This is the most flexible move. Black does
not rush into castling queenside. Now Ne2 is no longer as effective.} (9... Ng6
10. a4 $5 (10. Ne2 dxe4 11. dxe4 Bc5 $11) 10... a5 {This inclusion usually
favours White due to b5 square. It also prepares Ra3 for the future.} 11. O-O
O-O 12. Ne2 Ba7 13. c3 Nd7 14. Bc2 e5 15. Qf3 $14 {[%cal Ge2g3] White has
managed to achieve his idea regrouping of pieces.}) (9... O-O 10. Ne2 Bb6 11.
c3 $14 {We will continue with Bc2 and 0-0 next.}) 10. O-O {Black was ready to
meet Ne2 with a quick Bb6-c7. We first castle giving Black a few options.} (10.
Ne2 Bb6 $1 11. c3 dxe4 12. dxe4 Bc7 13. f4 {runs into the amazing} g5 $3 14.
Qxg5 Rg8 15. Qh5 Rxg2 $132) 10... O-O (10... Ng6 11. Kh1 $5 $36 {[%cal Gf2f4]})
(10... Qb6 11. a4 a5 {This inclusion is usually in our favour.} 12. exd5 Nxd5
13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Ra3 $1 Be5 15. Qg4 O-O 16. Rb3 Qc7 17. Re1 $14 {[%cal Gb3b5]}
) 11. Ne2 Bb6 12. c3 {[%cal Gd1c2,Gd3d4] Given time we will have a very
pleasant position with the bishop pair.} e5 $1 (12... Bc7 13. f4 $14) 13. Bc2
$146 (13. exd5 {1/2-1/2 (24) McShane,L (2682)-Yuffa,D (2577) Khanty-Mansiysk
2019} Nxd5 $11) 13... f5 $1 {Black has to play energetically too.} (13... Bc7
14. h4 $14 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gc1g5]}) 14. Bg5 Qe8 15. Rad1 Kh8 $1 {[%cal Gf5f4]
Black is preparing to go f4 next. We need to open up the position for our
bishops.} (15... f4 16. Qg4 {[%cal Gg4e6]} Kh8 17. exd5 cxd5 18. d4 $14) 16.
exd5 Nxd5 17. d4 Qh5 18. Rfe1 f4 19. Qh4 Qxh4 20. Bxh4 Rae8 $11) 8... exd5 (
8... cxd5 $2 {is bad after} 9. Nb5 $18) 9. O-O {What is our idea? Well first
of all we have the bishop pair which is a big trump. So we do not need to go
crazy to get an edge. We plan to go Bd1, Ne2 followed by d4 getting control
over the centre. Next, we usually go for c3, Bc2.} Nd7 (9... Ne7 10. Qg4 $5 {
Is an interesting extra option.} (10. Bd1 O-O 11. Ne2 Bb6 12. d4 Nd7 13. c3 Bc7
14. Qf3) 10... c5 $1 {is the best clearing the c6 square for the knight.} (
10... Bf6 {gives us a nice edge after} 11. d4 O-O 12. Bd3 $14) 11. b4 {We have
to play energetically.} h5 12. Qh4 Bf6 13. Qf4 cxb4 (13... c4 14. b5 $14 {
[%cal Gc1a3]}) 14. Qxb4 Nbc6 15. Qb5 (15. Qb3 Rb8 16. Ba3 g6 17. Rab1 O-O 18.
Rfe1 $13 {The position remains complex and unbalanced. You can check this out
further.}) 15... O-O 16. Ba3 Nd4 $1 17. Qd3 Nxe2+ 18. Qxe2 Re8 19. Bxe7 Rxe7
20. Qxh5 Bxc3 $11 {Black should be able to equalise.}) 10. Bd1 Ne7 11. Ne2 {
Now Black has two different options.} Be5 $1 {The bishop is much better on the
b8-h2 diagonal.} (11... Bf6 {This looks natural but it is slightly inaccurate,}
12. d4 O-O (12... Nf5 13. Qg4 g6 14. c3 $14 {[%cal Gd1c2]}) 13. c3 {We just
want to go Bc2 next followed by Qg4, Ng3 and play on the kingside. The bishop
is misplaced on f6 restricting Black's pieces.} Re8 (13... Nf5 14. Qf3 g6 15.
g3 Re8 (15... Bg5 16. Nf4 $1 {Of course we do not want to trade the bishops.}
Re8 17. h4 Bh6 18. Bc2 $14) 16. h4 {We stop all kinds of Bg5 ideas and also
prepare to go for h5 in the future.} Be7 $1 {Black finally admits his mistake
and regroups the bishop.} 17. Bc2 (17. h5 Nd6 18. Kg2 $14) 17... Ng7 18. Re1
Nf6 19. Bd2 Qd7 20. Nf4 Qg4 21. Qxg4 Nxg4 22. a4 $14 {We have a slight edge in
the endgame. We want to go b4-b5 next.}) 14. Bc2 Ng6 15. Be3 {We want to bring
the a1 rook into the game quickly.} (15. Qd3 Bg5 $1 (15... Qc7 {1-0 (47)
Tomczak,J (2584)-Socko,B (2636) Kruszwica 2022} 16. Ng3 Be7 17. Nf5 Bd6 18. g3
$16) 16. f4 Be7 $11) 15... Nb6 16. b3 Nc8 {Black wants to go Nd6-e4.} 17. Qg4
Nd6 18. Ng3 {We are in time to stop it and now he is stuck without a good plan.
} Bh4 19. Nf5 Ne4 20. c4 $14) 12. Qf3 O-O 13. d4 {He has to make one more
decision regarding the bishop.} Bc7 (13... Bd6 {Again, this looks very natural
but it is an inaccuracy. Black needs the d6 square for the queen or the knight.
} 14. c3 {Our play remains the same everywhere.} Ng6 15. Bc2 Re8 (15... Qf6 16.
Qg4 $1 {We do not want to exchange the queens yet as Black's pieces are still
uncoordinated and we can make use of this in the middlegame. Bg5 is a threat
now.} (16. Qxf6 {1-0 (61) McShane, L (2655)-Ghasi, A (2485) London 2021}) 16...
Qd8 17. Bg5 Nf6 18. Qf3 Be7 19. Ng3 $14 {The knight is getting to f5.}) (15...
Nf6 {runs into} 16. Bg5 $1 h6 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Qxf6 gxf6 19. Rae1 $14) 16. Ng3
(16. g3 {is also possible but less ambitious.} Qf6 17. Kg2 Qxf3+ 18. Kxf3 $14)
16... Qc7 17. Nf5 Bf4 18. Ne3 $1 {No we do not want to exchange the bishops.
Now we will go g3, h4 and the bishop will be pushed back to an unfortunate
square.} Nf6 19. g3 Bh6 20. h4 $14) 14. c3 {This transposes to the main line.}
Nf6 15. Bc2 Ng6 {This is a more harmonious development for Black with the
queen being able to jump to d6 anytime.} 16. Bg5 {We go for the same Bg5 again
but this is a better version for Black.} (16. g3 {is a good alternative. We
play slowly preparing to go h4-h5 in the future.} h6 (16... Ne4 $5 17. Bxe4
dxe4 18. Qxe4 f5 19. Qe6+ Kh8 $44) 17. h4 Re8 18. Be3 Ne4 19. Qg4 {[%cal Gh4h5,
Ge2f4]} Re6 $1 20. h5 Nf8 {Black keeps everything in control.} 21. Nf4 Bxf4 22.
Bxf4 Qb6 $11) 16... Qd6 17. Ng3 $5 {We want to take on f6 now and also keep an
eye on the e4 square.} (17. g3 {This looks great for us as we want to take on
f6 next and get a nice edge.} Ne4 $1 {A very important resource.} 18. Bxe4 dxe4
19. Qxe4 Rae8 20. Qf3 Qe6 21. Nf4 Bxf4 22. Bxf4 Nxf4 23. Qxf4 Qxh3 24. Rfe1 {
All of this happened in the game 1-0 (83) Tomczak,J (2584)-Socko,B (2636)
