interesting prophylactic move. Now Black cannot play c5 without allowing Nb5.
So he has to waste more time.} (10. g3 c5 11. Qg2 Nc6 12. f4 e5 $11) (10. h4 {
is also possible here.}) 10... Nbd7 {This is a concession but he has forced us
to go Na3.} (10... c5 11. Nb5 $1 $16) (10... O-O 11. g3 c5 12. Qg2 {Now that
Black has castled we do not need to rush with Nb5.} Nc6 13. f4 $14 {[%cal
Ga3c4]}) (10... a6 11. Nc4 b5 {The move b5 helps us play on the queenside with
a4 in the future.} 12. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gg2g3,Gf3g2,Gf2f4]}) 11. h4 $5
{This is the other plan which we saw- getting the queen to h3.} h5 12. Bg5 Qe7
13. Nc4 a5 (13... Ne5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Qh3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 14. c3 (14.
Rab1 $5 {is also possible preparing c3 slowly.}) 14... Ne5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16.
Rac1 $14 {[%cal Gc1c2,Gf3h3,Gf2f4]}) 9. d3 Bd6 10. g3 {The same plan as
earlier. We want to go Qg2 followed by f4 next.} e5 (10... O-O {Very logical
but we get a big edge after the simple} 11. Qg2 e5 12. f4 Qc7 13. f5 $1 $16 {
Now g4-g5 is going to be very dangerous for Black. We are clearly better.} b5
14. a4 a6 15. g4 c5 16. g5 Ne8 17. axb5 $18 {1-0 (34) Liang, A (2589)-Smith, D
(2047) Chess.com INT 2019}) 11. Qg2 {We are slowly preparing to go f4.} h6 {
1-0 (49) Konstantinov, M (2442) -Rodrigues,A (2280) LSS email 2017} (11... Bc7
{f4 is not as effective with the king still in the centre but we have a lot of
useful waiting moves to play. Another point behind this move was to meet c3
with Nc5. We do not hurry.} 12. Nd2 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd2f3]} (12. f4 Qe7 $11) 12...
h5 13. a4 $14 {[%cal Gd2c4]}) 12. c3 {With the bishop on d6 this is very
strong. Black is forced to release the tension or further weaken his queenside
with the move c5.} (12. f4 Bc7 $11) 12... c5 13. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gf2f4]})
(7... Be7 $5 {This is clever not allowing us to go for d4 so easily. We can
still do but it loses a tempo.} 8. d3 {I like to keep the game more complex
and it helps that it has not been played too much.} (8. Rd1 d4 $11 {0-1 (38)
Tomczak,J (2584)-Socko,B (2636) Kruszwica 2022}) (8. d4 dxe4 9. Qe3 (9. Nxe4
Qxd4 10. Nxf6+ {1-0 (56) Ragger, M (2669)-Postny, E (2615) Germany 2021} Bxf6
11. Rd1 Qa4 $11) 9... Nbd7 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 Nf6 12. Qd3 O-O {This is
still pleasant for White and something which we can go for.}) 8... O-O (8...
Nbd7 9. Qg3 O-O 10. Kh1 {[%cal Gf2f4] We want to go f4 next. Practically I
really like our position and it has a lot of potential.} b5 $1 {[%cal Gb5b4]
The best way to create counterplay.} (10... a5 11. f4 Ne8 12. a4 Kh8 13. Be3
$14) (10... Ne8 11. f4 f5 {1/2-1/2 (47) Gurgenidze,B-Khalilbeili,S Yerevan 1959
} 12. e5 $14) (10... Kh8 11. f4 Nc5 12. e5 Ne8 13. Nb1 $1 {A very nice idea to
bring the knight to f3. We are much better.} (13. d4 {0-1 (36) Guo, A (2358)
-Visakh, N (2516) Chess.com INT 2020})) 11. e5 Ne8 12. d4 {[%cal Ge2d3]} Qb6 (
12... b4 13. Na4 g6 14. c4 $1 {A very important move to bring the knight back
into the game.} dxc4 15. Bxc4 Nb6 16. Nxb6 Qxb6 17. Be3 $14) 13. Be3 g6 14. Bd3
Ng7 15. Ne2 $14 {We have regrouped our pieces and can soon start our play on
the kingside.}) 9. g4 $5 {This has been played only twice but I like this idea
of putting maximum pressure on Black. I have analysed a lot of different
options here and I did not find any clear way to equalise.} Ne8 {Once Black
removes his knight from f6 we can build up our center.} (9... dxe4 {This
happened in one of the games.} 10. dxe4 Nfd7 11. Qg2 e5 12. g5 $14 {White got
a nice edge in the game 1/2-1/2 (68) Moussard,J (2632)-Suleymanli,A (2541)
Riga 2021.}) (9... a5 {Is one of the top choices of the computer but it does
not achieve much.} 10. Qg3 {[%cal Gf2f4]} (10. Qg2) 10... a4 11. a3 Ne8 12. f4
f5 13. Bf3 $14) (9... Nbd7 10. Qg2 {We want to go f4 next and it makes a lot
of sense once Black has already committed his other knight to d7.} d4 11. Nb1
e5 12. f4 $14) (9... Kh8 10. h4 {[%cal Gg4g5]} (10. Qg3 {1-0 (41) Malicka,M 
(2275)-Panek,B (2152) Krakow 2023}) 10... Nbd7 11. g5 Ne8 12. Qh3 $14 {[%cal
Gf2f4]}) 10. d4 a5 11. a3 Nd7 12. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Gc1f4]}) (7... Nbd7 {This is
the most played move but it gives us a very pleasant middlegame after-} 8. d4
dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Nf6 (10... Be7 11. Rd1 O-O {Here we should go
either Bf4 or Qe3 to prevent the exchange of dark-squared bishops.} (11... Bg5
12. d5 $16) 12. Qe3 (12. c3 Bg5 13. f4 Bh6 14. g3 g6 $11 {1-0 (47) Nakamura, H
(2736) -Harikrishna,P (2730) chess24.com INT 2021}) (12. c4 Bg5 $1) (12. Bf4 $5
{Now Bf5 is no longer effective and we also have control over the h2-b8
diagonal.} Nf6 (12... Re8 13. Qf3 Nf8 14. Qb3 Ng6 15. Be3 Rb8 16. a4 $14) 13.
Qf3 Nd5 14. Bd2 Bg5 15. Be1 $14 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gc2c3,Gg2g3,Gh3h4] We get the
typical middlegame with the bishop pair.}) 12... Nf6 (12... Qc7 {Now Bg5 is no
longer an issue.} 13. Qf3 Nf6 14. c3 a5 15. g3 $14) 13. Bf3 Qc7 14. Qe2 Rfd8
15. g3 {The usual rule in these positions is to put pawns in the colour of the
opponent's bishop to restrict it. This will help us dominate the other colour.}
Rd7 16. c3 a5 17. Kg2 Rad8 18. Be3 $14) 11. Qd3 Be7 {here we can go for c4
plan or the usual c3 slow plan} (11... Bd6 12. c3 {White's plan here is to
play g3,Qf3 Rd1/e1.Kg2 and slowly improve the position. Black usually breaks
with e5 or c5.} O-O (12... Qc7 13. g3 O-O 14. Rd1 Rad8 15. Qf3 Rfe8 16. Bg5 Be7
17. Bf4 Bd6 18. Be3 e5 19. dxe5 Bxe5 {1/2-1/2 (72) Vachier Lagrave,M (2784)
-Artemiev,V (2716) Chess.com INT 2020} 20. Bc4 $16) 13. g3 h6 14. Qf3 a5 15. a4
{This inclusion I feel is in our favour since we can get control over the b5
square when he breaks with c5.} Qe7 16. Be3 c5 17. Bb5 cxd4 18. Bxd4 $14) 12.
Rd1 {I like also the plan with the move c4. This is more dynamic and opens up
the position. It depends on your personal choice.} (12. a4 a5 (12... O-O 13. a5
Qc7 14. c3 Rfd8 15. Qf3 $14) 13. c3 {This is the usual plan to keep the centre
secure.} O-O 14. Re1 Nd5 15. Qg3 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Ge7g5] We never allow Black
to trade the bishops easily.} Qc7 16. Qf3 Rfd8 17. Bd3 $14) 12... O-O 13. c4
Qc7 14. Be3 Rfd8 15. Bf3 e5 {Black had to do something as otherwise we just
have very good control over the centre along with the bishop pair.} (15... h6
16. g3 Rd7 17. Rac1 $14) 16. Qc2 exd4 17. Bxd4 {These endgames will not be
easy to defend for Black.}) 8. Rd1 {This is the point of our system- we want
to get the move d4 with a tempo.} Bd4 {Black tries to stop the move d4 in a
very unconventional way. We need to dislodge the bishop from d4.} (8... d4 {
does not work due to} 9. e5 $1 Nfd7 (9... dxc3 10. exf6 Qxf6 11. Qxf6 gxf6 12.
bxc3 {This endgame is bad for Black with the semi-open 'b' file and the bishop
pair.} Bd6 13. c4 Nd7 14. d4 b6 15. a4 $16) 10. Ne4 Be7 11. Qg3 O-O 12. d3 $16
{1/2-1/2 (48) Nepomniachtchi, I (2784)-Ding, L (2791) chess24.com INT 2020}) (
8... e5 {This is too ambitious with the king still in the centre.} 9. exd5 cxd5
10. d4 $1 exd4 11. Bb5+ $1 {We do not let him castle so easily.} Nc6 12. Re1+
Kf8 (12... Be7 13. Ne2 $16) 13. Ne2 $14) 9. Qf4 $1 {We do not mind him winning
the pawn on e4 as he needs to give us his important dark-squared bishop to
achieve that.} Bxc3 {Black has to take up the challenge. As they say, better
not suffer for free.} (9... Nbd7 {loses a pawn after} 10. exd5 Be5 11. Qb4 cxd5
12. d4 Bc7 13. Qxb7 $16) (9... Nxe4 {This just gives us very easy play.} 10.
Nxe4 dxe4 11. Qxe4 Qb6 12. Qf4 c5 13. c3 Bf6 14. a3 $1 {A very nice plan
preparing the move b4.} O-O 15. b4 $14) (9... e5 {These moves rarely work with
the king in the centre. We were trying to provoke such a response from Black
to open up the centre.} 10. Qg3 O-O (10... dxe4 11. d3 $1 {We will thank Black
for opening up the 'd' file for our rook.} exd3 12. Bxd3 Nbd7 {Happened in the
game 1-0 (19) Vachier Lagrave, M (2775)-Navara, D (2734) Riga 2019 and White
could have got a winning advantage after-} 13. Qxg7 Rg8 14. Qh6 $18) 11. d3 Kh8
12. Bf3 $14 {Next on the agenda is Bg5 putting more pressure on the d5 pawn.
We can also continue with Ne2 kicking the bishop out.}) 10. bxc3 {We want to
get our bishop to a3 very soon, keeping the black king still in the centre.}
Nxe4 11. Ba3 (11. Rb1 $5 {has been played a few times and is also interesting.}
) 11... Nd7 (11... Qa5 12. Bb4 Qb6 13. d3 (13. Rab1 {1/2-1/2 (58) Lucas,A 
(2299)-Alcala Gonzalez,C (2157) Barcelona 2021}) 13... Nf6 14. Bd6 $18 {
Rb1 is coming up next.}) 12. Rab1 Qa5 (12... b5 13. c4 $1 {Material is the
last thing on our mind here. We want activity for our pieces.} bxc4 14. Rb7 Qc8
(14... Qf6 $5 15. Qc7 $1 {Again we do not mind even giving up the 'f' pawn.}
Qxf2+ 16. Kh2 Rd8 17. d3 $14) 15. Rc7 Qd8 16. Rxc6 Qa5 17. d3 Qxa3 18. dxe4 O-O
19. exd5 exd5 20. Rxd5 Nb6 21. Rg5 $14 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gh3h4] White had a very
dangerous initiative in the game 1/2-1/2 (24) Williamson, H (2504)-Yeo, G 
(2477) ICCF email 2021}) (12... b6 13. c4 $1 Qf6 14. Qe3 Qg5 15. f4 Qg3 16. Bf3
{Black is in a lot of trouble. There have been two blitz games played here.
Let's take a look at them briefly.} O-O-O (16... g5 17. cxd5 (17. Bxe4 Qxe3+
18. dxe3 dxe4 $11 {1/2-1/2 (55) Jones, G (2688)-Vaibhav, S (2597) chess24.com
INT 2020}) 17... cxd5 18. Qd4 $16 {[%csl Re8]}) 17. Bb4 {The start of a very
cunning manoeuvre.} Kc7 18. d3 Nd6 19. Be1 $1 Qg6 20. a4 Rhe8 21. a5 Rb8 22.
Bf2 Qf6 23. Qd2 Red8 {All of this happened in the game 0-1 (40) Samusenko, M 
(2461) -Rozum, I (2529) Sochi 2021 and White could have maintained his huge
edge with} 24. cxd5 exd5 25. Rdc1 {[%cal Gc2c4]}) 13. Rb3 $146 {This has never
been played before. I have always really wanted to get this position on the
board particularly because of the top choice of many computers and the very
natural 13...e5.} (13. Bb4 Qa4 $1 (13... Qd8 {1-0 (37) Vachier Lagrave,M (2780)
-Mamedyarov,S (2772) Moscow 2019}) 14. f3 a5 15. fxe4 axb4 16. exd5 cxd5 17.
Rxb4 Qa7+ $11) 13... Nec5 {Black tries to block the diagonal to be able to
castle kingside.} (13... Ndc5 14. Bb4 $16 {[%csl Rc5,Re4][%cal Gb3b1]}) (13...
O-O-O {A very interesting pawn sacrifice.} 14. Qxf7 Nec5 $1 15. Bb4 (15. Ra1 $5
{A nice exchange sacrifice but it is not needed.} Nxb3 16. axb3 h5 17. Qxg7 $44
) 15... Qc7 16. Ra3 Rdf8 17. Qe7 Re8 {We have a few options here. I am not
giving too many details as I think this is very unlikely to happen and we do
not need to overload ourselves.} 18. Qh4 (18. Qxg7 Ne4 $13) 18... Ne4 19. Rxa7
$36) (13... e5 14. Qh4 $1 Ndc5 $6 {Many engines claim that Black is fine
initially but White has this amazing resource starting with} (14... Ndf6 15.
Bf3 $14) 15. d3 $1 Nxc3 (15... g5 16. Qh5 Nxb3 17. Bb4 $18) 16. Bh5 $3 {
A bolt from the blue. There is no way to defend.} Nxd1 (16... O-O 17. Bb4) 17.
Bxf7+ Kd7 18. Be6+ $1 Kxe6 19. Rxb7 $18) 14. Bb4 Qd8 15. Rbb1 {He still cannot
castle. d4 is always in the air. It is really hard to play with Black in these
positions.} b6 (15... Qf6 16. Qe3 {[%csl Rc5]} Na4 (16... b6 17. d4 Ne4 18. c4
$14) 17. Ba3 b5 18. c4 $1 {Black is forced to either open up the 'b' file or
the diagonal for the bishop.} bxc4 (18... dxc4 19. Bf3 Rc8 20. Qxa7 $16) 19.
Rb7 Nab6 20. Rb1 $16 {We can go d3 next. Hard to see Black's plan here.}) 16.
Qe3 Nb7 {Finally Black is in time to go c5 follwoed by 0-0. We are going to do
as much damage as possible by then.} 17. d4 c5 18. dxc5 Nbxc5 (18... bxc5 19.
Ba3 $16) 19. c4 $1 O-O 20. cxd5 exd5 {There are a few ways here to win back
the pawn and keep posing problems for Black.} 21. Qa3 {[%cal Gc2c4,Gd1d5]} (21.
Bf3 {is possible} Rc8 22. Bxd5 Re8 23. Qg3 $14) 21... a5 (21... Qc7 22. Rxd5
Nf6 23. Rd4 Qe5 24. Bxc5 bxc5 25. Rd2 $14 {The bishop is the better minor
piece in these positions.}) 22. Bc3 {This is safer and was my main line.} (22.
Be1 {is also something which you can explore. I will just give some of my
lines.} Nf6 23. Bf3 Rc8 24. Bxd5 (24. c4 d4 25. Qb2 d3 26. Qxb6 a4 $1 27. Ba5
Qd4 $11) 24... Nxd5 25. c4 Rc6 26. cxd5 Rg6 27. Rbc1 {[%cal Gc1c4,Ga3f3]} Qd7
$1 28. Qf3 Qa4 29. Qe2 Re8 $13) 22... Ne4 23. Ba1 Qc7 24. Qb2 Ndf6 25. Qxb6 {
We finally win the pawn back and get into an endgame.} (25. Rxd5 Nc3 26. Rg5
Nfe4 $13) 25... Qxb6 (25... Qxc2 26. Bd3 $14) 26. Rxb6 Rfc8 27. Rdb1 Kf8 28.
Bd3 {I believe that there is still some precision needed from Black to
equalise completely.} *

