{[%evp 0,37,20,19,65,45,45,31,31,40,40,5,15,16,21,-13,-6,-29,23,5,18,18,20,7,
21,-4,-3,18,17,11,23,23,23,19,7,-10,16,-7,0,-6]} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 dxe4
{Nowadays this is the most common response from Black across all levels. It is
not a big surprise since it is the easiest to play as Black and he does have a
lot of options here. Most people go for similar lines against the 3.d4 system 
(Nf6 lines).} 4. Nxe4 Nf6 (4... Bf5 {This is common among lower-rated players
who have not studied the openings properly.} 5. Ng3 Bg4 (5... Bg6 {This is bad
here compared to the 3.d4 variation as the knight is already on f3.} 6. h4 h6
7. Ne5 Bh7 8. Qh5 $1 {The point. Black is forced to defend f7 awkwardly.} g6 9.
Bc4 e6 10. Qe2 $18) 6. Bc4 {Both Ne5 and Bf7 are threats here.} e6 7. c3 Nf6 8.
O-O Nbd7 9. d4 Be7 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 $14 {We have the bishop pair and a
pleasant advantage.}) (4... Bg4 {This is rarely a good idea to give up the
bishop pair voluntarily.} 5. h3 Bxf3 (5... Qd5 6. Nd6+ {A nice intermediate
move.} exd6 (6... Qxd6 7. hxg4 $16) 7. hxg4 Qe4+ 8. Qe2 Qxe2+ 9. Bxe2 $16) 6.
Qxf3 Nd7 7. d4 Ngf6 8. Nxf6+ Nxf6 9. Bc4 {We are daring Black to take our pawn
on d4.} (9. c3 {is good enough for a small edge.} Qd5 10. Be2 $14) 9... Qxd4 (
9... e6 10. c3 $14) 10. Qb3 {The following line is more or less forced for
both sides.} e6 11. Qxb7 Qe4+ 12. Be3 Rd8 13. Bd3 Qb4+ 14. Qxb4 Bxb4+ 15. Ke2
$14 {We have a nice edge in the endgame.}) (4... Nd7 {This is quite slow. We
are in time to develop all our pieces comfortably.} 5. Bc4 Ngf6 (5... e6 6. d4
$14) 6. Neg5 e6 7. Qe2 {Now Nxf7 is a big threat. This is a better version of
the 3.d4 4...Nd7 line since we have managed to get our queen to e2 in time.}
Nd5 (7... Nb6 $6 {Allowing the knight to e5 is not a great idea.} 8. Ne5 Nxc4
9. Qxc4 $16) 8. d4 Be7 9. O-O h6 10. Ne4 O-O 11. Re1 $14 {Blacks problems are
due to the bishop on c8. We have much more space and better-placed pieces.}) 5.
Qe2 {This may come as a surprise to a few people. We do not want to take on f6
and free up Black's development. We want to force Black to help us bring our
queen out to the centre. This contradicts one of the general principles- Do
not bring your queen out too early. However, with all of the other Black
pieces still in the back rank, he cannot exploit it. In this chapter, we will
look at the alternatives to Nxe4 which is the main line.} Bf5 {Black forces us
to do what we want to do anyway.} (5... Qd5 6. Nxf6+ {I think if given the
option we should take on f6 damaging Black's pawn structure. He cannot do much
with the 'g' file.} gxf6 7. g3 {This is a common development scheme once we
have played the move Qe2.} Na6 8. a3 $1 {Important to stop Nb4.} (8. Bg2 $6 Nb4
9. d3 Bg4 $15 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gg4f3]}) 8... Bf5 9. d3 Nc5 {1/2-1/2 (59) Nabaty,T 
(2559)-Bartel,M (2665) Plovdiv 2012} 10. Bg2 $16) (5... Bg4 6. h3 {We can take
on f6 with check anytime. We first ask Black to decide on what to do with his
bishop.} Bh5 (6... Nxe4 $2 7. hxg4 $18) (6... Bxf3 {This is played less often
and for good reason. You should not give up bishops this easily.} 7. Nxf6+ gxf6
8. Qxf3 Qd5 9. Be2 Nd7 10. a4 e6 11. a5 $14 {I like gaining space on either
side of the board. White is slightly better.}) 7. Nxf6+ gxf6 8. d3 e6 9. Bd2 {
We are ready to g4 next.} Na6 (9... Be7 10. g4 Bg6 11. Bg2 $14) 10. a3 {
We often meet Na6 with a3. We do not allow the knight to harass us on b4.} Nc5
11. Qe3 Bg6 12. g3 $14 {White has a comfortable, small edge.}) (5... Na6 {
This is a cunning move which has been played by a few good players. Black
wants to get his knight to b4/c5 without blocking the light-squared bishop.} 6.
a3 {Has been played in only a couple of games. It was a novelty when I had
analysed it earlier. This is the only occasion where I do not want to force
gxf6.} (6. Nxf6+ {Is the main line and certainly possible. But this is
probably the best version of these lines Black can get.}) (6. d3 {This is a
very safe way of playing and was my backup against strong players. White gets
a very small edge which should most likely lead to a draw,} Nxe4 7. dxe4 e5 8.
Qd2 $1 {The only way to fight for something.} Qxd2+ 9. Bxd2 Nc5 10. Nxe5 Nxe4
11. Bc4 Nd6 12. Bb3 f6 13. Nf3 Bd7 14. O-O-O O-O-O 15. Rhe1 Re8 $11) 6... Nxe4
(6... Nc7 7. d4 Nxe4 8. Qxe4 Qd5 9. Qxd5 Nxd5 10. c4 Nf6 11. Bd3 $14 {We are
slightly better in the endgame with more space and better control over the
centre. Our king will be more active.}) (6... Bf5 {Happened in both games. We
are happy to now force gxf6.} 7. Nxf6+ gxf6 8. d3 $14 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gf1g2]}) 7.
Qxe4 Qd5 {This is very similar to the main line with the inclusion of a3 and
Na6. White does not want to trade the queens.} 8. Qe3 (8. Qh4 Nc5 9. Bc4 Qe4+
10. Qxe4 Nxe4 11. d3 Nd6 12. Bb3 h5 {This is quite pleasant for us. You can go
for this if you want to be solid.}) 8... Nc7 9. Be2 Qe6 {Black is desperate to
force the trade. We cannot say no now but we can ensure that he improves our
pawn structure with Qxe3.} 10. O-O Qxe3 11. fxe3 f6 12. d4 $14 {We have good
control over the centre and the pawn structure is interesting. I would pick
White here.}) 6. Nxf6+ gxf6 7. d3 Nd7 {Black's idea is to go Ne5 next. There
are a few different ways to deal with it.} 8. a4 $5 $146 {A novelty. What is
the point? Well, I just want to gain space on the queenside with a5 next. It
is also a bit of prophylaxis because we are expecting the move Ne5 and in
those lines, a4 is more useful.} (8. Bd2 {Is possible if you want to preserve
pieces on the board- playing against someone very positional.} h5 9. O-O-O (9.
g3 Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Bh6 $13) 9... h4 10. Kb1 Nb6 11. Rg1 Qd6 12. g4
hxg3 13. hxg3 O-O-O $13) (8. g3 {is the main move in the position. I will just
give some of my analysis here. This is not my main recommendation.} Ne5 9. Nxe5
Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Qxe5 11. Qxe5 (11. Bc3 Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2 h5 13. h4 Kd7 14. O-O Re8 $1
{[%cal Ge7e5]}) 11... fxe5 12. Bg2 h5 13. a4 Be6 (13... a5 14. b4 $14) 14. Ke2
f6 15. a5 Bd5 16. Be4 $14 {White has a very pleasant endgame although Black
should of course hold with precise play.}) 8... Ne5 {This is the key idea
behind Black's previous play.} (8... Bg4 {Again just gives us a pleasant edge
with the pair of bishops.} 9. a5 a6 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 e6 12. Bd2 $14) 9.
Nxe5 Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Qxe5 11. Qxe5 fxe5 12. a5 $1 {We do not even give Black the
option to go a5 himself. In addition to the space we also get the option to go
Ra4 next.} e4 $1 {This is the best way to fight for equality. Black eliminates
his weak pawn on e5.} (12... f6 13. Ra4 h5 14. Be2 $14) 13. dxe4 Bxe4 14. O-O-O
O-O-O 15. a6 {This pawn will keep creating problems for Black in the future.
Of course, it is a doubled-edged sword since it can easily become a weakness.}
b6 16. Re1 Bd5 17. h4 Rg8 18. f3 {White maintains a slight pull in the endgame.
Black cannot go for the a6 pawn anytime soon.} h5 19. Rg1 $14 {[%cal Gf1d3,
Gc2c4]} *

