{[%evp 0,33,19,8,59,45,64,40,40,40,42,21,36,34,66,38,36,52,9,22,28,4,21,6,32,
72,72,49,56,67,52,57,54,59,46,55]} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6
5. Qe2 Nxe4 {The most common move trading off the knights without damaging the
pawn structure. There are both advantages and disadvantages to bringing the
queen out this early. Black will gain a couple of tempi but we can create some
quick play with our pieces.} 6. Qxe4 {In this chapter we will look at a couple
of sidelines before moving on to the two main moves- Nd7 and Qd5.} Qa5 $5 {
The third most popular move in the position. What is the point of this move?
Black wants to go either Bf5 or Qf5 and harass our queen. He also copies us in
bringing the queen out early.} (6... Be6 {This is a strange move but Black
wants to get his bishop to d5 before finishing his development. Also, he wants
to get Nd7 without blocking the bishop.} 7. Be2 $5 {This has been played very
few times. We just want to finish our development.} (7. b3 {is the main move
with many games}) (7. d4 Bd5 {[%cal Gd5f3]}) 7... Nd7 (7... g6 8. Qe5 $16) (
7... Bd5 {Has been played only once in an online blitz game.} 8. Qe3 {The
queen is very well placed here. We will go b3, Bb2 next.} Nd7 {Black should
keep the e6 square open for the bishop.} (8... e6 9. d4 (9. O-O {1-0 (59)
Kollars, D (2598)-Grigorov, G (2507) Lichess.org INT 2021}) 9... Bd6 10. Nd2
$14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc2c4]}) 9. b3 Qb6 $1 (9... e6 {Once we have played the
move b3, e6 makes more sense. There is no quick Nd2, c4 plan.} 10. O-O Bd6 11.
d4 O-O 12. Bb2 Qc7 13. g3 Nf6 14. c4 $14 {We have a decent edge due to our
centre.}) 10. Bb2 {We do not mind the exchange on e3.} (10. d4 g6 11. Bb2 Bg7
12. O-O O-O 13. c4 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 {This is pleasant for White but not easy to
make progress.}) 10... Qxe3 11. fxe3 f6 12. c4 Bf7 13. d4 $14 {This is similar
to 6. ..Qa5 lines and we are more pleasant in this endgame.}) 8. d4 {With the
knight on d7 blocking the 'd' file we can go for the move d4. Now we are
looking to build a good centre and also use our queen to create play on the
kingside.} Nf6 (8... g6 9. c4 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Qh4 Bf5 12. Rd1 $14 {[%cal
Gg2g4,Gf3g5] The queen is perfect on h4 to create an attack on the kingside.})
(8... Qa5+ 9. c3 Bf5 10. Qh4 e6 11. O-O (11. Qg3 {[%csl Rg7] is also good} Nf6
12. Ne5 $14) 11... Bd6 12. Bf4 Bxf4 13. Qxf4 O-O 14. h4 $14 {g4 is a threat
now and we are slightly better.}) 9. Qe5 $1 $146 {The queen is perfect here.
Black has a difficult decision to make regarding the development of his pieces.
} Bg4 (9... Qd6 10. O-O $14) (9... g6 {looks natural but runs into} 10. Ng5 $1
Bf5 11. g4 Bd7 12. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7]} e6 {Black is forced to weaken a lot of
squares.} 13. Bf4 $16) (9... Qd7 10. c3 Nd5 11. O-O f6 12. Qg3 Qc7 {Black
manages to exchange queens but he will continue to suffer in the endgame.} 13.
Bd2 $14) 10. h3 Bh5 11. O-O e6 {Black is finally able to play e6 but he has
wasted a tempo.} 12. Bf4 {We maintain full control over the h2-b8 diagonal.}
Be7 13. c4 O-O 14. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5,Ge5e3] We want to gain space on the
queenside now. g4 and Qe3 may follow next. White has a nice edge in the
position.}) 7. b4 $1 {Now we are the ones harassing our opponent's queen. We
gain useful space on the queenside and also the b2 square for the bishop.} (7.
Bc4 {is the main line} Bf5 8. Qf4 e6 9. O-O Be7 10. d3 Qd8 11. Re1 O-O $11 {
[%csl Gf5][%cal Gb8d7]}) (7. Qf4 Qf5 $1 {transposes to 6...Qd5 lines.}) 7...
Qd5 8. Qe3 {Of course, we do not want to exchange the queens on d5 or e4. We
do not mind exchanging them on e3, improving our pawn structure in the process.
} Bf5 (8... Qe6 9. Be2 {As mentioned, we are happy to trade queens on e3. It
opens up the 'f' file for our rook and helps us get better control over the
centre.} Qxe3 10. fxe3 Bf5 (10... f6 11. a3 {A nice prophylactic move.} e5 12.
d4 exd4 13. exd4 Be6 14. Bf4 Nd7 {Happened in the game 1/2-1/2 (80) Jones, G 
(2683)-Howell, D (2676) London 2019 and White would have been better after} 15.
c4 $14) 11. d3 e6 12. Bd2 $14 {White had a nice edge and went on to win in the
game 1-0 (56) Zelbel, P (2448) -Svane,R (2613) Magdeburg 2020.}) 9. c4 Qe4 10.
Be2 {We are threatening to decline the trade of queens with Qb3/c3 next. Black
does not have a great choice.} Qxe3 (10... e6 11. Qc3 Qc2 {Black still has to
try to exchange the queens as otherwise we will create a pretty dangerous
initiative against Black's king.} 12. Bb2 Qxc3 13. Bxc3 {This way we have got
our bishop to its ideal square on c3 for free.} Be7 14. h4 {Now we gain space
on the other side of the board.} Nd7 (14... h5 $2 15. Bxg7 $1 Rg8 16. Bc3 Rxg2
17. Nd4 $16 {[%csl Rh5]}) 15. Nd4 {The bishop does not have a good square to
go to.} O-O 16. h5 {There is some sadistic pleasure in delaying Nxf5 for as
long as possible :)} h6 17. Nxf5 exf5 18. Bd3 f4 {Doubled pawns are usually
not great when they are pushed ahead and the f4 pawn is a big weakness.} 19.
Bf5 Nb6 20. d3 $14 {If given the chance we want to go a4 next. We have a
decent edge with the bishop pair.}) 11. fxe3 Nd7 {This happened in one of my
games back in 2021. My opponent surprised me with the Carokan but this idea
was quite easy to remember.} (11... e6 {allows us to directly go} 12. b5 $1 a6
$1 {Black has to fight back on the queenside.} (12... cxb5 {runs into} 13. Nd4
$1 bxc4 14. Nxf5 exf5 15. O-O {The bishop pair in such an open board are
monsters to deal with.} g6 16. Bxc4 $14) 13. bxc6 Nxc6 14. O-O Be7 15. a4 {
A cunning move preparing to go Ba3 next. It is not easy for Black to continue
precisely here.} a5 $1 {Black is ready to meet Ba3 with the annoying Nb4.} (
15... O-O-O 16. d4 {[%cal Gc1a3] We will follow up with Ba3 and get a nice
edge with a great centre.}) (15... O-O 16. Ba3 Rfe8 (16... Nb4 17. a5 $1 $16)
17. d4 {[%cal Gc4c5] This is quite a bit better for us and c5 is coming up
very soon.}) 16. d4 (16. Ba3 Nb4 $1) 16... O-O 17. c5 b6 $1 18. cxb6 Rfb8 19.
Nd2 Rxb6 20. Nc4 {[%cal Ge2f3,Ge3e4] We still have some pressure in the
position although it should be equal with correct play.}) 12. O-O (12. b5 {
Is also challenging for Black.} e5 13. O-O Bg6 14. a4 {[%cal Gc1b2]}) (12. Bb2
{is the simple approach} e6 13. a3 Be7 14. Bc3 O-O 15. d3 {[%csl Gd3,Ge3][%cal
Ge1d2] with a pleasant endgame.}) 12... e6 13. b5 {We need to play dynamically
here. We are preparing to go Nd4 next.} cxb5 (13... Bg6 $1 {A good
prophylactic move. We have two different ways to pose problems here.} 14. Nh4 (
14. a4 $5 a5 $1 {A very important move for Black as he needs to stop our play
on the queenside. Now things are not that easy for us.} (14... Be7 15. a5 $14)
15. d4 c5 $1 {Again this is necessary to fight back against our center.
Otherwise, we would have gone for the move c5 ourselves.} 16. Bb2 f6 $11) 14...
cxb5 15. cxb5 Bb4 $1 {Black has to keep an eye on the d2 pawn.} (15... Be7 16.
Nxg6 hxg6 17. Bb2 Bf6 18. Bxf6 Nxf6 19. Rac1 $14 {[%cal Ge2f3]}) 16. a4 Bc2 {
[%csl Gc2]} 17. Nf3 Rc8 18. a5 {[%cal Gc1b2] White still has some initiative
and Black has to defend accurately.}) 14. Nd4 $1 {This is the point behind the
move b5.} Bg6 (14... bxc4 15. Nxf5 exf5 16. Bxc4 $14) 15. Nxb5 Kd8 16. d4 a6
17. Nc3 $14 {And I got a nice edge which I converted after a lot of
difficulties in the game 1-0 (46) Arjun, K (2503) -Vaishali, R (2393)
Barcelona 2021.} *

