{[%evp 0,33,16,15,68,61,40,42,42,42,42,19,34,41,22,22,22,22,20,3,-6,1,-2,9,11,
18,16,20,37,21,25,30,68,66,61,61]} 1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6
5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Nd7 {This is the most popular move in the position.
Earlier I used to believe that Qd5 was the critical move and this gives White
very comfortable play after Bc4, Ne5. However, after some new developments, it
is not easy at all to pose any problems there. On the flip side for Black the
lines with d4 are pretty one-sided with only White having chances to push. It
is relatively risk-free.} 7. d4 {I like this more since it does not force
matters and leads to more strategic positions. It is pretty natural too,
gaining space in the center. It is not as popular as the Bc4 system.} (7. Bc4 {
This is the first variation I learnt in this entire system.} Nf6 8. Ne5 {
Pretty cool forcing Black to play e6 and shut down the bishop on c8. I have
been hoping someone takes on e4 even in a blitz game without any luck :)} e6 9.
Qe2 b5 $1 {This has become very popular in recent times and it more or less
equalises by force in most of the lines.} ({Normal play with moves such as} 
9... Bd6 {give White a pleasant edge.} 10. d4 O-O 11. O-O Qc7 12. Bf4 b6 13.
Rad1 Bb7 14. Rfe1 $14) 10. Bd3 Qc7 11. a4 $1 Bd6 $1 12. Nxc6 b4 13. Nd4 {
[%cal Gd4f5,Gd4b5]} a6 14. Nf5 Be5 $1 {Black gives up the pawn on g7 but he
gets enough counterplay in return. I have given all the main lines of my
analysis. I do not think White has anything objectively and it is
unfortunately pretty forcing. However, you can definitely prepare and go for
this if you are playing with someone who is not good in openings.} (14... Bb7
15. Nxd6+ Qxd6 16. O-O $14 {This at least gives us some chances to convert our
extra pawn.}) 15. Nxg7+ Kf8 16. Nh5 Nxh5 17. Qxh5 Bb7 18. Be2 (18. Qh4 Rg8 19.
Qxb4+ (19. Bxh7 Rxg2 $11) 19... Bd6 20. Qc3 Bxg2 21. Rg1 Qxc3 22. bxc3 Bxh2 23.
Ba3+ Ke8 24. Rxg2 Rxg2 $11) 18... Bxg2 (18... Rc8 $2 {1-0 (59) Zelbel,P (2448)
-Donchenko,A (2657) Magdeburg 2020} 19. c3 $16) 19. Rg1 Rg8 20. d4 Bxh2 (20...
Bxd4 21. Bh6+ Ke8 22. Rd1 $13) 21. Qh6+ Ke8 22. Qxh7 Ke7 23. Bh5 Raf8 24. Bxf7
Rh8 25. Qg7 (25. Bg5+ Kd6 26. Qxh2+ Rxh2 27. Bf4+ Kc6 28. Bxc7 Kxc7 29. Bg6 Bd5
30. b3 Rfxf2 $11 {1/2-1/2 (43) Ragger,M (2682)-Donchenko,A (2595) Brest 2019})
25... Bd5 26. Bg8+ (26. Bh5+ Kd6 27. Qxc7+ Kxc7 28. Rg7+ Kc6 29. Be2 Bf4 30.
Bxf4 Rxf4 $11) 26... Ke8 27. Qxh8 Bxg1 28. Qh5+ Kd7 29. Be3 Bxf2+ 30. Bxf2 Qf4
31. Qh4 Qxh4 32. Bxh4 Rxg8 $11) 7... Nf6 {Now there are several different
options to choose from. I will recommend two different options. Both of them
give us a pleasant position without much risk. I feel here it is more
important to understand the typical ideas and play some training games rather
than concrete preparation. I will highlight some of the typical ideas and
plans in the position.} 8. Qd3 {[%cal Gb3f7] This is the main move in the
position. What are the pros and cons? The queen can head to b3 next and will
be well placed along the a2-g8 diagonal. The dark-squared bishop can be
developed freely. On the flip side, our light-squared bishop cannot get to c4
and Blakc can get Bf5 with a tempo.} (8. Qh4 Bf5 $11) (8. Qf4 {This was the
main line in my preparation for the last couple of years. I do not have it as
my main line partly because Adhiban recommends it in his course (not in too
much detail though). The advantage of Qf4 is that now we can continue with Bc4
and 0-0 which would be our ideal development plan. The drawback is that it is
more vulnerable here and both Qd6 and Nd5 are very interesting.} Nd5 {The most
played move in the position exploiting the queen on f4.} (8... e6 {As usual
this is pretty sad for Black.} 9. Ne5 Bd6 10. Bd2 {We want to castle long and
just checkmate Black.} O-O 11. O-O-O Nd5 12. Qe4 f5 13. Qe1 $16) (8... g6 {
This is also a bit passive and allows us to develop all our pieces comfortably.
} 9. Bc4 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 {There are several ways to continue here. Our
next moves will usually include h3, c3, a4 and maybe Qh4, Qg3.} Nd5 (11... Qd6
12. Qh4 $14) 12. Qg3 Bf5 13. c3 a5 14. a4 Qd6 15. Qh4 e6 16. h3 $14) (8... Qd6
$5 {This has been played very few times but is one of the best ways to
continue for Black.} 9. Bd3 {We allow Black to trade off the queens but gain
some tempi.} (9. Ne5 {This is possible but now Black can continue with} g6 {
and meet} 10. Bc4 {with} Be6 $1 $11) 9... Qxf4 (9... Qe6+ 10. Qe5 Nd5 11. Bd2
$14 {This is a better version of the endgame.}) 10. Bxf4 Bg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4h5,
Ge7e6] This is quite annoying and solid for Black.} (10... g6 11. h3 Bg7 12.
O-O-O $14) 11. Ne5 Bh5 {Now there are a few ways to continue but Black is very
solid and it is difficult to pose serious problems, On the other hand, it is a
completely risk-free position for us.} 12. Bd2 {This is a kind of prophylactic
move against Nd5. We will let Black decide how he wants to continue.} e6 (12...
Rd8 13. c3 e6 14. h4 $14) 13. a4 {We want to go a5.} Nd5 (13... Bd6 14. a5 a6
15. O-O $14) (13... Bg6 14. a5 $14) (13... a5 $6 14. Nc4 $16) 14. g4 (14. a5 $6
f6 $1 15. Nc4 Bg6 $11) 14... Bg6 15. h4 Bxd3 16. Nxd3 h5 17. g5 {We gave some
pressure in this endgame with more space.}) 9. Qd2 $1 {A strange square but we
want to meet Bf5 with Bd3.} Bf5 {Black wants to go e6 and complete his
development next.} (9... g6 {again leads to comfortable play after} 10. Bc4 Bg7
11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 $14) 10. Bd3 {This does usually favour the side with less
space but does have some benefits too. It enables us to finish development
faster and get better control over the centre.} Bxd3 11. Qxd3 e6 12. O-O Bd6
13. c4 {I think this is the only way to keep posing problems for Black.} Ne7
14. Bd2 {The bishop will be perfect on c3 keeping an eye on d4 and hinting at
going d5 at the right moment.} O-O 15. Qe4 Qd7 16. a4 $14 {A very typical move
gaining space on the queenside. White has a slight edge.}) 8... g6 {By far the
main move in the position. Black wants to get the move Bf5 and also fianchetto
his dark-squared bishop.} (8... e6 {This is very passive and allows us to get
everything we want.} 9. Bf4 {The bishop is well placed along this diagonal.}
Be7 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Nd5 12. Bg3 $16) (8... Bg4 $5 {This looks strange
inviting the move Ne5 but Black wants to get the bishop to h5 and g6
eventually. It is a typical idea to get the bishop out before going for the
move e6. It is much less popular than the move g6.} 9. Ne5 Bh5 10. c3 e6 11.
Qh3 {Now Bc4 is a big threat.} Bd6 $146 (11... Qd5 $6 {Was played by Gukesh
but it is a mistake allowing White to get a few tempi in.} 12. Be3 Be7 13. Bc4
Qe4 14. Bd3 Qd5 15. O-O O-O 16. Bg5 $16 Bg6 17. Bxg6 hxg6 18. f4) 12. Bd3 Qc7
$1 {Again this was important to stop us from going Bg5.} (12... O-O 13. Bg5 $14
Bg6 14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. Qh4) 13. Nc4 O-O (13... Be7 14. Bg5 Bg4 15. Qg3 Qxg3 16.
hxg3 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gf2f3]}) 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Qg3 Qxg3 16. hxg3 {We get a
pleasant endgame with the bishop pair. Of course, Black is very solid but it
is only White who can keep trying.} Bg6 17. Be2 {[%csl Gc1,Ge2]}) 9. Be2 Bg7 (
9... Bf5 10. Qb3 Qb6 11. c3 Be4 {[%cal Gb6b3,Ge4f3] Black wants to give up the
bishop pair on f3 and trade queens. The resulting endgame is very solid for
him.} (11... Qxb3 12. axb3 a6 13. b4 {[%cal Gb4b5]}) 12. Qa4 $5 {We do not let
him trade queens so easily.} (12. O-O Qxb3 13. axb3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 a6 $11) 12...
Bg7 13. O-O O-O 14. Ne5 Rfd8 15. Qa3 {I think our position is quite pleasant
and we have a slight edge. Black has not managed to equalise in the centre and
the bishop on e4 is a bit stuck.}) 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 {There have been quite
a few top-level games here and White seems to always get a slight edge out of
the opening. Although the results seem to favour Black.} Bf5 {The bishop gains
a tempo but it does not do much on f5.} (11... a5 {Black wants to get a4 and
Bf5 not allowing the queen to settle on b3.} 12. a4 {We immediately stop the
plan.} (12. Qa3 {1/2-1/2 (65) Jones, G (2684)-Keymer, V (2607) Malmo 2021} Qd6
$11) 12... Qb6 {Black stops Qb3 but the queen is not doing much on b6.} 13. c3
Bf5 14. Qd1 Bg4 (14... Rad8 15. h3 c5 16. dxc5 Qxc5 17. Qb3) 15. Ne5 Bxe2 16.
Qxe2 Rad8 {1/2-1/2 (64) Bjerre, J (2612)-Keymer, V (2700) Germany 2022} 17. Bg5
Rfe8 18. h3 $14) 12. Qb3 Qb6 (12... Qc7 13. h3 {This is always useful,
clearing the back rank and covering the g4 square.} (13. a4 $5) 13... Be6 14.
c4 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5] Next we will try to go a4-a5 and get a firm grip on the
queenside. Black should not let that happen.} (14. Qe3 $5 Nd5 15. Qd2 $14)
14... b5 $1 15. Qc2 bxc4 16. Bxc4 {The c6 pawn is going to be a long-term
problem for Black.} Bxc4 (16... Bd5 17. Ne5 $14) 17. Qxc4 Rac8 18. Bd2 e6 19.
Rac1 Qb7 {1/2-1/2 (57) Frolyanov,D (2521)-Khegay,D (2523) Kazan 2022} 20. Ne5
$1 $14) 13. c3 {We are ready to jump with Ne5 at the right moment.} Bg4 (13...
Rfe8 {1-0 (105) Rapport,R (2763)-Asadli,V (2579) Baku 2021} 14. Ne5 (14. Qd1 $5
Rad8 15. Bc4 e6 16. Qe2 $14) 14... Be6 15. Bc4 {We are happy to trade the
bishops off as it strengthens our control over the centre.} Bxc4 16. Nxc4 $14)
14. Qc2 {As we saw earlier if Black manages to take on f3 and b3 the resulting
endgame is very drawish.} (14. h3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Qxb3 (15... e6 {1/2-1/2 (70)
Caruana,F (2835)-Bluebaum,M (2660) chess24.com INT 2020}) 16. axb3 e6 $11)
14... Rfd8 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 e6 17. g3 $14 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gg1g2,Gh3h4] We
have the bishop pair and a slight edge in the position.} *

