{[%evp 0,41,16,15,74,40,42,42,42,42,42,23,36,42,53,35,57,55,71,56,54,34,46,16,
29,35,61,69,45,38,75,28,21,27,16,15,15,-1,-14,-51,-37,-36,-25,-32]} 1. e4 c6 2.
Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Qe2 Nxe4 6. Qxe4 Qd5 {In my mind this was
always the main line in the 3...dxe4 variation but I think its popularity has
come down slightly over the last few years. Black chases our queen around to
exchange it. We have two major options- Qf4 and Qh4. I have analysed both of
them pretty deeply. I mostly played Qh4 and I will have it as my main line. It
is safer while Qf4 usually involves a pawn sacrifice.} 7. Qh4 {We are
preparing the move Bc4 followed by 0-0. Black has to try and exchange queens.}
(7. Qe3 Bf5 $11) (7. Qf4 Qf5 (7... Qd6 $5 {This has rarely been played but it
looks pretty interesting as I could not find an easy way to keep queens on the
board.} 8. d4 Qxf4 9. Bxf4 Bf5 {[%cal Ge7e6]} 10. O-O-O {White is probably
still slightly better here.} e6 11. Nh4 Be4 12. Re1 Bg6) 8. Qe3 Qxc2 {Black
asks us to prove our compensation for the pawn. I was not too comfortable in
these positions as I tend to value material highly.} (8... Qe6 {This is the
most played move but it is not principled and gives us a slight advantage.} 9.
b3 Qxe3+ 10. fxe3 Bf5 11. Bb2 Nd7 12. O-O-O e6 13. Re1 $14 {[%cal Ge3e4]}) 9.
Bd3 Qa4 10. O-O {This is a critical position. I will give some of my analysis
here without comments. You can check it out on your own.} (10. b3 Qa5 11. Bb2
Na6 $11) 10... Qb4 (10... Nd7 11. b3 Qb4 {tr} 12. Bb2 Nb6 13. Ne5 (13. Be4 $5
Qd6) 13... Nd5 14. Qe2 Be6 (14... Nf4 15. Qf3 $18) 15. Rac1 {[%cal Gc1c4]} Nf4
16. Qe3 Nxd3 17. Nxd3 Qb6 18. Bd4 Qd8 19. Nc5 Qc8 20. Nxe6 Qxe6 21. Qxe6 fxe6
$11) 11. a3 (11. b3 Nd7 (11... f6 {1-0 (57) Giri,A (2761) -Bluebaum, M (2663)
Chess.com INT 2022} 12. Re1 Qb6 13. Qf4) (11... Be6 $5)) 11... Qb6 12. Qf4 Qd8
13. Bc4 e6 14. d4 Bd6 15. Qg4 O-O 16. Re1 (16. Bh6 Qf6 17. Bg5 Qf5 18. Qxf5
exf5 19. Rfe1 Nd7 20. Be7 Bxe7 21. Rxe7 Nb6 22. Bb3 Rb8 23. Ng5 Nd5 24. Bxd5
cxd5 25. f4 h6 26. Nf3 Be6 27. Rc1 Rfe8 28. Rxe8+ Rxe8 29. Rc7 Rb8 $11) 16...
Nd7 17. Bg5 Nf6 18. Qh4 Be7 19. Re5 (19. Bd3 g6 20. Bh6 Re8 21. Ne5 Nd5 $11)
19... Kh8 20. Bd3 g6 $11) 7... Qe6+ (7... Bf5 {is just slightly worse after} 8.
Bc4 Qd6 9. d3 e6 10. Bf4 Qb4+ {This is too greedy.} (10... Qd8 11. Qg3 $14) 11.
c3 (11. Bd2 {Rozum,I (2596)-Manush,S (2352) IND 2019}) 11... Qe7 (11... Qxb2 $2
{loses to} 12. O-O Qxc3 13. Rab1 b5 14. Bxb5 cxb5 15. Rfc1 $18) 12. Qg3 Nd7 13.
Nh4 $16 {We will go 0-0 next and get a big edge.}) (7... Qf5 $5 {This is very
rare. Black is preparing to go Qg4 and we have to decide how to deal with the
pawn on c2.} 8. d3 {This has been played only once.} (8. Bc4 Be6 $1) 8... Qg4
9. Qxg4 Bxg4 10. Be2 Nd7 11. h3 {We want to win the bishop pair. If Black
retreats there is a good chance that the bishop will get misplaced.} Bxf3 (
11... Bh5 12. Be3 e6 13. g4 Bg6 14. a4 $14) 12. Bxf3 e6 13. Bf4 (13. Bd2 $5 Ne5
14. Bh5 g6 15. Be2 $14) 13... h5 14. Ke2 {Black is solid but we can keep
pushing with moves like a4, g4 next.}) 8. Be2 Qg4 {This is the main move,
exchanging the queens.} (8... Qg6 {Again we have an option of giving up a pawn
or playing it safe. We can afford to waste a tempo here not giving up the pawn
but I will give you both options.} 9. Qc4 {The added benefit of this move is
that it has not been played much.} (9. O-O {This is a more principled option.}
Qxc2 (9... Qg4 {is a full tempo down.} 10. Qxg4 Bxg4 11. h3 Bf5 12. d3 $14) 10.
Bc4 Qf5 11. Re1 {The queen is much better on h4 than on f4 which we saw
earlier. Now there is a forcing line starting after the move Nd7.} Nd7 (11...
e6 12. d4 Nd7 13. Qg3 Qg6 14. Ng5 $14 {[%cal Gc4d3]} Be7 15. Bd3 Qh5 16. f4 {
[%cal Gf4f5]}) 12. Ng5 (12. d4 Nb6 13. Bb3 f6) 12... Ne5 13. Rxe5 {All of the
next few moves are forced for Black.} Qxe5 14. Bxf7+ Kd8 15. Bc4 Ke8 16. h3 {
Clearing the back rank and preparing to get our other pieces into the game.}
Bf5 17. d3 Qe1+ 18. Kh2 e6 19. g4 Qe5+ 20. Kg1 Bg6 21. Nxe6 Kd7 22. Bf4 $36 {
The position is quite complex but it is clear that we are the ones with the
initiative and Black has to be careful.}) 9... Nd7 {Black does not take the
bait and now we have a typical slightly better middlegame.} (9... Qxg2 {
Black still tries to win material but this gives us a lot of tempi.} 10. Rg1
Qh3 11. Ng5 Qf5 12. d4 e6 13. Rg3 $1 {Black should be very careful here and
give back the pawn with} Be7 14. Rf3 Qd5 15. Nxf7 O-O 16. Ne5 $14) 10. O-O Nb6
11. Qb3 Qe6 12. Qe3 {We want to exchange the queens only on our terms.} Qxe3 (
12... Nd5 13. Qxe6 Bxe6 14. d4 $14) 13. fxe3 Bg4 14. h3 Bh5 15. g4 {The bishop
is going to be misplaced there on g6.} Bg6 16. d3 $14) 9. Qg3 {A familiar
concept. We want to trade queens on our terms only. In this case, opening up
the 'h' file for our rook.} (9. Qxg4 {Is also possible. There have been very
few games here. It is quite solid for Black though.} Bxg4 10. h3 Bh5 (10... Bf5
11. d3 g6 {[%cal Gf8g7]}) 11. d3 f6 12. Be3 Nd7 13. a4 a5 {Looks close to
equal although White is more pleasant.}) 9... Qxg3 (9... g6 10. Ng5 Qxg3 11.
hxg3 {Transposes}) 10. hxg3 g6 {The most played move and probably the best for
Black. It's better to keep the h3-c8 diagonal open for the bishop.} (10... h6
11. b3 Bf5 12. Bb2 $14) (10... Bf5 {This is one of the most played moves in
the position but I think that it is a slight inaccuracy. Black's play is slow
and the bishop on f5 is not stable.} 11. b3 $1 {The pawn on c2 is not really
hanging here. We want to go Bb2 and 0-0-0 next.} Nd7 (11... a5 {is too slow}
12. Bb2 h6 13. O-O-O a4 14. Nd4 Bc8 15. f4 (15. Rde1 axb3 16. axb3 $14 {
Vachier Lagrave,M (2795)-Salem,A (2633) Moscow 2017}) 15... Na6 16. Rde1 $16 {
None of Black's pieces are properly developed while we are looking to start
our initiative with f5 and g4.}) (11... Bxc2 12. d3) 12. Bb2 e6 (12... Nf6 13.
O-O-O O-O-O $2 14. Ne5 Be6 15. Bc4 $18 (15. f4 {1-0 (129) Grabinsky, A (2350)
-Zhai, M (2365) Chess. com INT 2019})) (12... O-O-O $2 {is a big mistake due to
} 13. Ng5 Bg6 14. Bh5 $18) (12... e5 13. O-O-O Bd6 14. d4 e4 15. Nh4 Be6 16. d5
$1 {A very nice idea to open up the position and win one of the bishops.} cxd5
17. Nf5 $1 Bxf5 18. Rxd5 $16) 13. O-O-O (13. Nh4 Bxc2 14. d3 Nc5 15. Kd2 Bxd3
16. Bxd3 Rd8) 13... h6 14. Rde1 {Black is still not able to castle easily. We
have ideas of Nh4 and Bh5 exploiting the king on e8.} Rg8 (14... O-O-O $2 {
unfortunately fails to} 15. Ng5 $1 Bg6 16. Bd3 $18) (14... Bh7 15. g4 $16) (
14... Nf6 15. Ne5 Rd8 16. g4 Bh7 {1/2-1/2 (67) Bharath, S (2495)-Aronyak, G 
(2519) chess24.com INT 2022} 17. Nc4 $16 {We want to go f4 and g5 next.}) 15.
Nh4 (15. Nd4 $5 {is another decent alternative.} Bg6 16. g4 {We want to get f5
very quickly.} O-O-O 17. f4 Bd6 18. f5 exf5 19. gxf5 Bh7 20. Bh5 Rdf8 21. a4
Nf6 22. Bf3 Re8 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. g4 $14) 15... Bh7 16. Bh5 Ke7 {An
unfortunate necessity for Black.} 17. f4 $146 {We do not slow down. There are
other interesting ideas but this is the most direct.} (17. a4 $5) (17. Re3 {
also posed a lot of problems in 1-0 (37) Liang, A (2536)-Brattain, M (2364)
Saint Louis 2017}) 17... g5 $1 {It is important for Black to create some
counterplay.} (17... g6 18. Bg4 $16 {[%cal Gh4f3,Gf3e5]}) 18. fxg5 Rxg5 19. g4
Bg7 20. Ba3+ c5 21. Nf3 Rd5 {The rook is very unstable but there is no way to
trap it.} 22. g5 hxg5 23. Bxf7 Kxf7 24. Rxh7 $14 {White has a lot of pressure
in this endgame. Black has to play very accurately to defend.}) 11. Ng5 {
This is a tricky move which has not been played that often. We want to go Bc4
next and force him to make some weaknesses. The h7 pawn is not really hanging
but there are a few cases where we can get away with it.} Bg7 (11... f6 {
This does close down the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop.} 12. Ne4 Bf5 (
12... Bg7 13. g4 $14) 13. d3 Nd7 14. Be3 $14 {Martirosyan,H (2586)-Melkumyan,H
(2664) GEO 2018}) (11... Nd7 $146 {was one of the top choices of the computer
initially but it runs into} 12. Nxh7 $1 {We have to be well prepared to go for
this. RIght now Nf6 is a threat.} Bg7 13. Rh4 $1 f6 14. b3 $1 Nc5 (14... Kf7
15. Bb2 {[%cal Gf7g8,Ge2c4] We are in time now to go 0-0-0 and Rh1.}) (14... g5
15. Rh5 Kf7 16. Bb2 $16) 15. Ba3 (15. Bb2 $5) 15... Ne6 16. O-O-O Kf7 17. Rdh1
Bd7 18. Bb2 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] We will go f4 next and try to get in the
move f5. The knight on h7 helps us create some initiative on the kingside/
centre.}) (11... h6 {This is very natural and happened in one of my games. My
opponent was spending a lot of time on his moves.} 12. Bc4 e6 13. d4 Nd7 14.
Ne4 Bg7 15. Bd2 $5 $146 {A typical computer move. White is preparing to go Nd6
and Bb4.} (15. c3 f5 16. Nc5 $1 (16. Nd6+ {I went after the bishop pair but
the resulting position is very solid for Black.} Ke7 17. Nxc8+ Raxc8 {[%csl
Gc4,Ge6,Gf5,Gg6][%cal Gd7b6,Gb6d5,Gb7b5,Ga7a6]} 18. O-O Nb6 19. Bb3 {1/2-1/2 
(34) Arjun,K (2499)-Muthaiah,A (2401) Belgrade 2022} Nd5 $11) 16... Nxc5 17.
dxc5 {We are playing against Black's light-squared bishop.} Bd7 18. Be3 O-O-O
19. O-O-O $14 {One idea is to double on the 'd' file with Rd6. We can go f4
next and fix the weakness on e6.}) 15... Bxd4 (15... a5 16. g4 $14) 16. O-O-O {
We have a lot of activity to compensate for the missing pawn.} Bg7 17. g4 b6
18. g5 hxg5 (18... h5 19. a4 Ke7 20. Bf4 e5 21. Rhe1) 19. Rxh8+ Bxh8 20. Bxg5
$14 {[%cal Ge4d6] Black is unable to finish his development. We can go f4, g4
and f5 if given the chance. Bb7 will always be met with Nd6.}) 12. Bc4 e6 {
[%cal Gc2c3,Gg3g4,Ga2a4,Gh1h7] We have a variety of choices here. I will give
a few options. I always like lines which are a bit forcing and force our
opponents to make tough decisions. The drawback here is usually that Black
will completely equalise with precise play. But in modern chess, we cannot
expect anything more. I recommend two different options- the novelty a4 and
the more forcing Rxh7.} (12... f6 {blocks his own bishop on g7.} 13. Ne4 Bf5
14. d3 Nd7 15. a4 $14 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gc1e3]}) 13. Rxh7 $5 {Let us directly win
the pawn on h7. Now the game becomes a bit more concrete. This has happened in
two games by the same player as white..} (13. c3 c5 14. Ne4 Nd7 15. Bb5 b6 16.
d3 Ke7 17. Bg5+ f6 18. Bf4 e5 19. Be3 f5 20. Nd2 Bb7 $11) (13. g4 h6 14. Ne4
Nd7 15. c3 Ke7 16. b3 b6 17. Ba3+ c5 18. d4 Bb7 19. f3 Rac8 $11) (13. a4 $146
h6 (13... Nd7 14. a5 $14) (13... h5 14. a5 O-O 15. d3 Nd7 16. O-O $14) (13...
a5 $6 {Black stops our expansion on the queenside but this changes the
evaluation of the Rxh7 lines.} 14. Rxh7 $1 {Let us see the difference.} Rxh7
15. Nxh7 f6 16. g4 Kf7 17. g5 f5 18. Nf6 Nd7 19. Nxd7 Bxd7 {[%cal Ga8h8,Gh8h1]}
20. Ra3 $1 $14 {[%cal Ga3h3] This was not possible previously!}) 14. Ne4 Nd7
15. a5 {We managed to gain space on the queenside and also stop the plan of b6.
} (15. d3 b6 $11) 15... f5 $1 {This is the only way for Black to finish his
development.} (15... Ke7 16. d3 $14) 16. Nc3 Ne5 17. Be2 c5 18. d3 {We can
continue with Be3, Bf3 and I will definitely take White over Black. The pawn
on a5 is a big trump for us.}) 13... Rxh7 14. Nxh7 f6 15. g4 $1 {We can bring
the knight back. Black should not try to win the piece back desperately.} Kf7 (
15... g5 $6 {is a very natural human instinct to trap the knight but it just
does not work concretely due to our lead in development.} 16. d4 Na6 (16... Kf7
17. f4 {We can always defend the knight with Bd3.} Kg8 18. Bd3 $16) 17. f4 Nb4
{Happened in the game 1-0 (42) Solodovnichenko,Y (2577)-Mirzoev,A (2438) Dhaka
2021. White could have got close to a winning edge after.} 18. fxg5 $1 Nxc2+
19. Kd1 Nxa1 20. gxf6 Kf7 21. g5 $18) 16. g5 f5 17. Nf6 {Our knight is safe
but it still does not have any squares left. Black should not try to win back
the pawn immediately.} Nd7 (17... c5 18. Rb1 Nd7 $1 {Again Black trades off
the knight while also getting Bc8-d7.} (18... Nc6 19. f4 $14) 19. b4 cxb4 20.
Nxd7 Bxd7 21. Rxb4 Bc6 22. Bf1 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gb4h4] Again Black has decent
compensation for the pawn but he still has to prove it.}) (17... Bxf6 $6 18.
gxf6 Nd7 {Happened in the other game- 1/2-1/2 (96) Solodovnichenko,Y (2574)
-Lin,Y (2345) Lienz 2019.} 19. d4 Nxf6 20. Bf4 $16 {We are much better with
the bishop pair.}) 18. Nxd7 Bxd7 {[%cal Ga8h8,Gh8h1]} 19. Bf1 $5 {A nice
defensive resource. Black is going to make use of the open 'h' file and we
have to defend our kingside.} (19. d4 $5 Bxd4 (19... Rh8 20. c3 Rh1+ 21. Ke2 c5
22. dxc5 Bc6 23. g3 Be4 $44) 20. c3 Bg7 21. Be3 b6 $11) 19... Rh8 20. d3 c5 21.
c3 {We have managed to consolidate our position and maintain the extra pawn.
Black does have good compensation with his activity.} *

