{[%evp 0,23,-14,-20,20,21,21,6,14,14,14,11,11,12,12,12,34,19,8,7,8,-10,-4,-6,0,
-17] How to continue with White?} 8. a4 $5 $146 {A novelty. What is the point?
Well, I just want to gain space on the queenside with a5 next. It is also a
bit of prophylaxis because we are expecting the move Ne5 and in those lines,
a4 is more useful.} (8. g3 {is the main move in the position. I will just give
some of my analysis here. This is not my main recommendation.} Ne5 9. Nxe5 Qa5+
10. Bd2 Qxe5 11. Qxe5 (11. Bc3 Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2 h5 13. h4 Kd7 14. O-O Re8 $1 {
[%cal Ge7e5]}) 11... fxe5 12. Bg2 h5 13. a4 Be6 (13... a5 14. b4 $14) 14. Ke2
f6 15. a5 Bd5 16. Be4 $14 {White has a very pleasant endgame although Black
should of course hold with precise play.}) 8... Ne5 {This is the key idea
behind Black's previous play.} (8... Bg4 {Again just gives us a pleasant edge
with the pair of bishops.} 9. a5 a6 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 e6 12. Bd2 $14) 9.
Nxe5 Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Qxe5 11. Qxe5 fxe5 12. a5 $1 {We do not even give Black the
option to go a5 himself. In addition to the space we also get the option to go
Ra4 next.} e4 $1 {This is the best way to fight for equality. Black eliminates
his weak pawn on e5.} (12... f6 13. Ra4 h5 14. Be2 $14) 13. dxe4 Bxe4 14. O-O-O
O-O-O 15. a6 {This pawn will keep creating problems for Black in the future.
Of course, it is a doubled-edged sword since it can easily become a weakness.}
b6 16. Re1 Bd5 17. h4 Rg8 18. f3 {White maintains a slight pull in the endgame.
Black cannot go for the a6 pawn anytime soon.} h5 19. Rg1 $14 {[%cal Gf1d3,
Gc2c4]} *

